\id 1MA Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h 1 Machabees
\mt1 The First Book of Machabees.
\c 1
\p
\v 1 And it came to pass, after that Alexander Philip's son the Macedonian, that first reigned in Greece, being gone out of the land of Cethim, struck Darius king of the Persians and the Medes: \f + \fr 1:1 \ft Other Kings reigned before Alexander in Greece, but he was the first that reigned in that great Monarchy erected by himself.\f*
\v 2 he made many battles, and obtained the munition of all, & slew the kings of the earth:
\v 3 and he passed through even to the ends of the earth: and took the spoils of the multitude of the Gentiles: & the earth was silent in his sight.
\v 4 And he gathered power, and an army exceeding strong: and his heart was exalted and elevated:
\v 5 and he obtained the regions of the Gentiles, & the tyrants: and they were made tributaries to him.
\v 6 And after these things, he fell down in his bed, and he knew that he should die.
\v 7 And he called his servants the Nobles, that were brought up with him from his youth: & he divided his kingdom to them, when he yet lived. \f + \fr 1:7 \ft By delivering his ring to Perdicca, he gave him authority to distribute his kingdoms. Iustinus. li. 12. Q. Curtius. li. 10.\f*
\v 8 And Alexander reigned twelve years, & he died.
\v 9 And his servants possessed the kingdom, every one in his place:
\v 10 and they did all put crowns on them after his death, & their sons after them many years, & evils were multiplied in the earth. \f + \fr 1:10 \ft * li. 2. c. 3. v. 1. D\f*
\v 11 And there came forth of them a sinful root Antiochus Illustre, the son of king Antiochus, that had been at Rome an hostage: & he reigned in the hundredth & seven & thirtieth year of the kingdom of the Greeks. \f + \fr 1:11 \ft Epiphanes, Noble in renown.\f* \f + \fr 1:11 \ft This Antiochus began his reign in the year 137. from Seleucus the first King of Syria after Alexander: otherwise this was the 156 year of the Grecian Monarchy. Euse. in chronico.\f*
\v 12 In those days there went forth of Israel wicked children, & persuaded many, saying: Let us go, and make a covenant with the Gentiles, that are about us: because since we departed from them many evils have found us.
\v 13 And the talk seemed good in their eyes.
\v 14 And some of the people determined, & went to the king: & he gave them leave to do the justice of the Gentiles.
\v 15 And they built a school in Jerusalem, according to the laws of the Nations:
\v 16 and they made to themselves prepuces, and revolted from the holy testament, and were joined to the Nations, and were sold to do evil. \f + \fr 1:16 \ft * li. 2. c. 4. v. 7. F\f*
\v 17 And the kingdom was prepared in the sight of Antiochus, and he began to reign in the land of Ægypt, that he might reign over two kingdoms.
\v 18 And he entered into Ægypt with great multitude, with chariots, and elephants, & horsemen, and a copious multitude of ships:
\v 19 And he made war against Ptolomee the king of Ægypt, & Ptolomee was afraid at his presence, and fled, and many fell wounded. \f + \fr 1:19 \ft Being established in the kingdom of Syria, he coveted also the kingdom of Ægypt.\f*
\v 20 And he took the fenced cities in the land of Ægypt: and he took the spoils of the land of Ægypt. \f + \fr 1:20 \ft * li. 2. c. 4. v. 21. H\f*
\v 21 And Antiochus turned, after he struck Ægypt in the hundredth and three and fortieth year: and he went up to Israel,
\v 22 and went up to Jerusalem with a great multitude.
\v 23 And he entered into the sanctification with pride, & took the golden altar, & the candlestick of light, & all the vessels thereof, & the table of proposition, and the libatories, and the phials, and the little mortars of gold, and the veil, & the crowns, and the golden ornament, that was in the face of the temple: & he brake all into pieces. \f + \fr 1:23 \ft Iosephus li. 12. c. 6. writeth that Antiochus first killed such as would have hindered his entrance into Jerusalem, and afterwards those that opened the gates unto him, but would have hindered him from spoiling the temple.\f*
\v 24 And he took the silver and gold, & the desiderable vessels: and he took the hidden treasures which he found: & carrying away he departed into his own land.
\v 25 And he made a slaughter of men, and spake in great pride.
\v 26 And great lamentation was made in Israel, and in every place of theirs:
\v 27 and the princes, and the ancients mourned, and the young men, and the virgins were weakened, & the beautifulness of the women was changed.
\v 28 Every husband took lamentation: and the women that sat in the marriage bed mourned:
\v 29 and the land was moved upon the inhabitants therein, & all the house of Jacob did put on confusion.
\v 30 And after two years of days the king sent a Prince of tributes into the cities of Juda, and he came to Jerusalem with a great multitude. \f + \fr 1:30 \ft This was Apollonius, as appeareth li. 2. c. 5. v. 24.\f*
\v 31 And he spake unto them peaceable words in guile: and they believed him.
\v 32 And he fell upon the city suddenly, and struck it with a great plague, & destroyed much people in Israel.
\v 33 And he took the spoils of the city, and burnt it with fire, and destroyed the houses thereof, and the walls thereof round about:
\v 34 and they led the women captive, and the children, and the cattle they possessed.
\v 35 And they built the city of David with a great wall, and a strong, and with firm towers, and it was made a castle for them: \f + \fr 1:35 \ft The tower of Sion fortified & kept,\f*
\v 36 and they placed there a sinful nation, wicked men, & they waxed strong therein: And they laid armour, and victuals, and gathered together the spoils of Jerusalem: \f + \fr 1:36 \ft by a garrison of Macedonians.\f*
\v 37 and laid them up there: & they became a great snare.
\v 38 And this was made for an embushment of the sanctification, and to be an ill devil in Israel.
\v 39 And they shed innocent blood round about the sanctification, and contaminated the sanctification.
\v 40 And the inhabitants of Jerusalem fled by reason of them, and it became the habitation of strangers, and she became stranger to her own seed, and her children forsook her.
\v 41 Her sanctification was desolate as a wilderness, her festival days were turned into mourning, her sabbaths into reproach, her honours into naught.
\v 42 According to her glory was her ignominy multiplied, and her highness was turned into mourning.
\v 43 And king Antiochus wrote to all his kingdom, that all the people should be one: and every one should leave his own law. \f + \fr 1:43 \ft It sufficed not this cruel tyrant to spoil God's people of their goods, & many of their lives, but he also perverted many in religion: because his master the devil seeketh to destroy men's souls.\f*
\v 44 And all Nations consented according to the word of king Antiochus,
\v 45 & many of Israel consented to his service, & they sacrificed to idols, & defiled the sabbath.
\v 46 And the king sent books by the hands of messengers into Jerusalem, & into all the cities of Juda: that they should follow the law of the Nations of the earth,
\v 47 and should prohibit holocausts & sacrifices, & placations to be made in the temple of God,
\v 48 and should prohibit the sabbath to be celebrated, & the solemn days.
\v 49 And he commanded the holy places to be defiled, & the holy people of Israel.
\v 50 And he commanded altars to be built, and temples, and idols, & swine's flesh to be immolated, and common beasts,
\v 51 and to leave their children uncircumcised, and their souls to be contaminated in all uncleannesses, and abominations, so that they should forget the law, and should change all the justifications of God.
\v 52 And whosoever had not done according to the word of king Antiochus, they should die.
\v 53 According to all these words wrote he to all his kingdom: & he appointed princes over the people, that should force these things to be done.
\v 54 And they commanded the cities of Juda to sacrifice.
\v 55 And many of the people were gathered to them, they that had forsaken the law of our Lord: and they did evils upon the land:
\v 56 and they chased forth the people of Israel in hidden corners, and in the secret places of fugitives.
\v 57 The fifteenth day of the month Casleu, the hundredth five and fortieth year king Antiochus built the abominable idol of desolation upon the altar of God, and throughout all the cities of Juda round about they builded altars: \f + \fr 1:57 \ft Daniel's prophecy. ch. 9. was here in part fulfilled, as in a figure, & our Saviour confirmeth it. Mat. 24. of Antichrist setting up abomination of desolation in the holy place.\f*
\v 58 and before the gates of houses, and in the streets they burnt frankincense, and sacrificed.
\v 59 and the books of the law of God they burnt with fire, cutting them:
\v 60 and with whomsoever were found the books of the testament of our Lord, and whomsoever observed the law of our Lord, they murdered him, according to the edict of the king.
\v 61 In their power did they these things to the people of Israel, that was found in every month & month in the cities:
\v 62 And the five and twentieth day of the month they sacrificed upon the altar that was against the altar.
\v 63 And the women that circumcised their children, were murdered according to the commandment of king Antiochus,
\v 64 and they hang up the children by the necks throughout all their houses, and those that had circumcised them, they murdered.
\v 65 And many of the people of Israel determined with themselves, that they would not eat the unclean things: and they chose rather to die, than to be defiled with unclean meats:
\v 66 and they would not break the holy law of God, and they were murdered,
\v 67 and there was made great wrath upon the people exceedingly. \f + \fr 1:67 \ft * li. 2. c. 5. v. 11.\f*
\c 2
\p
\v 1 In those days arose Mathathias the son of John, the son of Simeon, Priest of the sons of Joarib from Jerusalem, & he sat in the mountain of Modin: \f + \fr 2:1 \ft The 2. part. The wars of the Machabees, begun by this Mathathias, and prosecuted by his sons, especially by Judas, as in the seven chapters following, and more largely in the second book from 8. chapter to the end of the last.\f*
\v 2 and he had five sons, John who was surnamed Gaddis:
\v 3 and Simon, who was surnamed Thasi:
\v 4 and Judas, who was called Machabeus:
\v 5 and Eleazar, who was surnamed Abaron: and Jonathan, who was surnamed Apphus.
\v 6 These saw the evils, that were done in the people of Juda, and in Jerusalem.
\v 7 And Mathathias said: Woe is me, wherefore was I born to see the affliction of my people, and the affliction of the holy city, and to sit there, when it is given in the hands of the enemies?
\v 8 The holy places are come into the hand of strangers: the temple thereof as an ignoble man.
\v 9 The vessels of her glory are carried away captive: her old men are murdered in the streets, and her young men are fallen by the sword of the enemies. \f + \fr 2:9 \ft This small help of great importance, is that aid whereof Daniel prophesied ch. 11. v. 34.\f*
\v 10 What nation hath not inherited her kingdom, and hath not obtained her spoils?
\v 11 All her beauty is taken away. She that was free, is made a servant.
\v 12 And lo our holies, and our beauty, and our glory is desolate, and the Nations have defiled them.
\v 13 Whereto then is it for us yet to live?
\v 14 And Mathathias rent his garments, and his sons: and they covered themselves with hair-cloths, and lamented exceedingly.
\v 15 And there came thither they that were sent from king Antiochus, to compel them that were fled into the city of Modin, to immolate and to burn frankincense, & to depart from the law of God.
\v 16 And many of the people of Israel consenting came to them: but Mathathias, & his sons stood constantly.
\v 17 And they that were sent from Antiochus answering said to Mathathias: Thou art the prince, and most honourable, and great in this city, and adorned with sons, and brethren.
\v 18 Therefore come thou first, and do the king's commandment, as all Nations have done, and the men of Juda, and they that are remaining in Jerusalem: & thou shalt be & thy sons among the king's friends, and amplified with gold, and silver, and many gifts.
\v 19 And Mathathias answered, & said with a loud voice: Although all Nations obey king Antiochus, that every man revolt from the service of the law of his fathers, and consent to his commandments:
\v 20 I and my sons, & my brethren will obey the law of our fathers.
\v 21 God be merciful unto us: it is not profitable for us to forsake the law, and the justices of God:
\v 22 we will not hear the words of king Antiochus, neither will we sacrifice, transgressing the commandments of our law, to go another way.
\v 23 And as he ceased to speak these words, there came a certain Jew in the eyes of all to sacrifice to the idols upon the altar in the city of Modin, according to the king's commandment.
\v 24 And Mathathias saw, & was sorry, and his reins trembled, and his fury was kindled according to the judgement of the law, and flying upon him he slew him upon the altar: \f + \fr 2:24 \ft Mathathias not of private spirit, but being general captain of the people, did this justice according to the law, where it is commanded to kill the authors of false pretended religion. Deut. 13. S. Cyprian. Exhort. ad Martyrium c. 5. S. Bernar. Epist. 158. ad Innocent.\f*
\v 25 yea and the man, whom king Antiochus had sent, which compelled them to immolate, he slew in that very time, & destroyed the altar,
\v 26 and zealed the law, as did Phinees to Zamri the son of Salomi. \x + \xo 2:26 \xt Num. 25.\x*
\v 27 And Mathathias cried out with a loud voice in the city, saying: Every one that hath zeal of the law, establishing his testament, let him come forth after me.
\v 28 And he fled himself, & his sons into the mountains, and left all things whatsoever they had in the city.
\v 29 Then came down many seeking judgement, and justice, into the desert:
\v 30 and they sat there themselves, and their children, and their wives, & their cattle: because the evils overflowed upon them.
\v 31 And it was reported to the king's men, and to the army that was in Jerusalem in the city of David, that certain men which dissipated the king's commandment, were departed into secret places in the desert, & many were gone after them.
\v 32 And forthwith they went forwards towards them, & set battle against them in the day of the Sabbaths,
\v 33 & they said to them: Do you resist now also as yet? Come forth: and do according to the word of king Antiochus, and you shall live.
\v 34 And they said: We will not come forth, neither will we do the king's word, to pollute the day of the Sabbaths.
\v 35 And they hastened battle against them.
\v 36 And they answered them not, neither did they cast a stone at them, nor stopped the secret places,
\v 37 saying: Let us die all in our simplicity: and heaven & earth shall be witnesses, upon us that you unjustly destroy us. \f + \fr 2:37 \ft These are commended by S. Ambrose li. 1. Offic. c. 40. and other Fathers, dying in the simplicity of doves, though they had not the prudence of serpents, which others observing are more commended, especially in respect of the whole Church so dangerously impugned, which God indeed will ever defend, and conserve from utter ruin: Yet he useth also ordinary means, by lawful wars and the like.\f*
\v 38 And they gave them battle on the Sabbaths: & there died they, & their wives, & their children, & their cattle even to a thousand souls of men.
\v 39 And Mathathias understood it and his friends, and they had lamentation upon them exceedingly.
\v 40 And every man said to his neighbour: If we shall all do as our brethren have done, and shall not fight against the heathen for our lives, and our justifications: now will they quickly destroy us from the earth.
\v 41 And they thought in that day, saying: Every man whosoever shall come unto us in battle on the day of the Sabbaths, let us fight against him: & we will not all die, as our brethren died in secret places.
\v 42 Then was there gathered to them the synagogue of the Assideans strong of force out of Israel, every voluntary in the law: \f + \fr 2:42 \ft Assideans, otherwise called Esseni, not hypocritically as the Pharisees, nor erroneously as the Sadducees, but sincerely professed a peculiar holy rule of life. Iosephus li. 2. c. 12. de bello Iudaico.\f*
\v 43 and all that fled from the evils, were added to them, and were made a strength to them.
\v 44 And they gathered an army, & struck the sinners in their wrath, and the wicked men in their indignation: & the rest fled to the nations to escape.
\v 45 And Mathathias went round about, & his friends, and they destroyed the altars:
\v 46 & they circumcised the uncircumcised children, as many as they found in the coasts of Israel: and in strength.
\v 47 And they persecuted the children of pride, and the work prospered in their hands:
\v 48 and they obtained the law out of the hands of the nations, and out of the hands of the kings: and they gave not the horn to the sinner.
\v 49 And the days of Mathathias approached to die, & he said to his sons: Now is pride strengthened, & chastisement, & the time of subversion, & the wrath of indignation:
\v 50 Now therefore o my sons, be ye emulators of the law, & give your lives for the testament of your fathers.
\v 51 And remember the works of the fathers, which they have done in their generations, & you shall receive great glory, and an eternal name.
\v 52 Abraham was he not in tentation found faithful, and it was reputed to him unto justice? \x + \xo 2:52 \xt Gen. 22.\x*
\v 53 Joseph in the time of his distress kept the commandment, & he was made Lord of Ægypt. \x + \xo 2:53 \xt Gen. 41.\x*
\v 54 Phinees our father, fervent in the zeal of God, received the testament of an everlasting Priesthood. \x + \xo 2:54 \xt Num. 25.\x*
\v 55 Jesus whilst he accomplished the word, was made the Duke in Israel. \x + \xo 2:55 \xt Iosue. 1\x*
\v 56 Caleb whilst he testifieth in the Church, received an inheritance. \x + \xo 2:56 \xt Num. 14.\x*
\v 57 David in his mercy obtained the seat of the kingdom for ever. \x + \xo 2:57 \xt 2. Reg. 2.\x*
\v 58 Elias whilst he zealeth the zeal of the law, was received into heaven. \x + \xo 2:58 \xt 4. Reg. 2.\x*
\v 59 Ananias and Azarias & Misael believing, were delivered out of the flame. \x + \xo 2:59 \xt Dan. 3.\x*
\v 60 Daniel in his simplicity was delivered out of the lions' mouth. \x + \xo 2:60 \xt Dan. 5.\x*
\v 61 And so think ye through generation & generation: that all that hope in him, are not weakened.
\v 62 And of the words of the sinful man be not afraid: because his glory is dung, and worm:
\v 63 today he is extolled, and tomorrow he shall not be found: because he is turned into his earth, & his cogitation is perished.
\v 64 You therefore my sons take courage, and do manfully in the law: because in it you shall be glorious.
\v 65 And behold Simon your brother, I know that he is a man of counsel: hear ye him always, and he shall be a father to you. \f + \fr 2:65 \ft In all affairs order is of singular importance, that every office be designed to fittest persons. As here Mathathias appointed Simon the chief for determining matters in counsel, & Judas the first for execution, & that the rest should obey these two, and each of these the other in his office.\f*
\v 66 And Judas Machabeus valiant of strength from his youth, let him be to you the prince of warfare, and he shall manage the battle of the people.
\v 67 And you shall bring to you all the doers of the law: and revenge ye the revenge of your people.
\v 68 Repay retribution to the Gentiles, & attend to the precept of the law.
\v 69 And he blessed them, and was laid to his fathers.
\v 70 And he died the hundredth & six and fortieth year, and he was buried by his sons in the sepulchres of his fathers in Modin, and all Israel lamented him with great lamentation.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 And Judas, that was called Machabeus his son arose in his stead: \f + \fr 3:1 \ft He did not arrogate to himself to be chief, but being designed by his father, was so accepted by his brethren, and the good people joined with them in defence of the law of God.\f*
\v 2 and all his brethren helped him, & all that had joined themselves to his father, and they fought the battle of Israel with joy.
\v 3 And he dilated glory to his people, & put on him a brigantine as a giant, and girded about him his warly armour in battles, and protected the camp with his sword.
\v 4 He became like a lion in his acts, and as a lion's whelp roaring in hunting.
\v 5 And he persecuted the wicked inquiring them out, & such as troubled his people, them he burnt with fire:
\v 6 and his enemies were repelled for fear of him, all the workers of iniquity were troubled: and salvation was directed in his hand.
\v 7 And he exasperated many kings, & rejoiced Jacob in his works, & for ever his memory is in benediction. \f + \fr 3:7 \ft Judas had four battles, and victories, against four general captains sent by King Antiochus Epiphanes. The first against this Apollonius.\f*
\v 8 And he walked through the cities of Juda, & destroyed the impious out of them, & turned away wrath from Israel.
\v 9 And he was renowned even to the uttermost part of the earth, and he gathered them that perished. \f + \fr 3:9 \ft li. 2. c. 8. v. 1. M\f*
\v 10 And Apollonius gathered together the Gentiles, and from Samaria a power much and great, to make battle against Israel.
\v 11 And Judas understood it, and went forth to meet him: and he struck, and killed him: and there fell many wounded, & the rest fled away.
\v 12 And he took the spoils of them, and the sword of Apollonius Judas took away, and he fought with it all his days.
\v 13 And Seron captain of the army of Syria heard that Judas gathered a congregation of the faithful, and an assembly with him, \f + \fr 3:13 \ft The second against Seron.\f*
\v 14 and he said: I will make me a name, and will be glorified in kingdom, and will overthrow Judas, and those that are with him that despised the word of the king.
\v 15 And he prepared himself: and there went up with him a camp of the impious strong helpers, to do vengeance upon the children of Israel.
\v 16 And they approached even as far as Bethoron: & Judas went forth to meet him with few.
\v 17 But as they saw the army coming to meet them, they said to Judas: How shall we a few be able to fight against so great a multitude & so strong, and we are wearied with fasting today?
\v 18 And Judas said: It is an easy matter for many to be inclosed in the hand of few, & there is no difference in the sight of the God of heaven to deliver in many, & in few. \f + \fr 3:18 \ft The natural frailty of man feareth to encounter with a strong enemy, but true confidence in God's help, which is ever assured in a good cause, giveth courage and getteth the victory.\f*
\v 19 Because not in the multitude of the army is the victory of battle, but from heaven is the strength.
\v 20 They come to us in an obstinate multitude, & in pride, to destroy us, & our wives, & our children, and to spoil us.
\v 21 But we will fight for our lives, & our laws:
\v 22 & our Lord himself will destroy them before our face, but you fear them not.
\v 23 And as he ceased to speak, he flew upon them suddenly: & Seron was destroyed, & his host in his sight:
\v 24 & he pursued him in the descent of Bethoron even to the plain, & there fell of them eight hundred men, & the rest fled into the land of the Philisthiims.
\v 25 And the fear of Judas & of his brethren, & the dread fell upon all the nations round about them.
\v 26 And his name came to the king, & all nations told of the battles of Judas.
\v 27 And as king Antiochus heard these words he was wrath in his mind: & he sent, & gathered the army of all his kingdom, a camp exceeding strong:
\v 28 and he opened his treasury, and gave wages to the army for a year: and he commanded them, that they should be ready at all assays.
\v 29 And he saw that money failed out of his treasures, & the tributes of the region small, because of the dissension, and the plague, that he had made in the land, to take away the ordinances, that were from the first days: \f + \fr 3:29 \ft Not only the Jews resisted Antiochus' innovations in religion, but also diverse other nations revolted and rebelled, because he commanded all to leave their former rites and gods, and to accept of his gods only. ch. 1. v. 43.\f* \f + \fr 3:29 \ft persecuting all that did not thereto conform themselves.\f*
\v 30 and he feared lest he should not have as once and twice, for costs & gifts, which he had given before with a large hand: & he had abounded above the kings, that had been before him.
\v 31 And he was exceedingly astonished in mind, and purposed to go into Persis, and to take the tributes of the regions, and to gather much silver.
\v 32 And he left Lysias a noble man of the blood royal, over the king's affairs, from the river Euphrates even to the river of Ægypt:
\v 33 and that he should bring up Antiochus his son, till he returned.
\v 34 And he delivered to him half the army, and Elephants: and he gave him commandment concerning all things that he would, and concerning the inhabitants of Jurie, and Jerusalem:
\v 35 and that he should send an army to them, to destroy and root out the power of Israel, and the remnant of Jerusalem, and to take away the memory of them out of the place,
\v 36 and that he should appoint inhabitants in all their coasts, children strangers, & should by lot distribute their land.
\v 37 And the king took the part of the army that remained, & went forth from Antioch the city of his kingdom in the year an hundreth and seven and forty: and he passed over the river Euphrates, & walked through the higher countries.
\v 38 And Lysias chose Ptolomee the son of Doryminus, and Nicanor, and Gorgias, mighty men of the king's friends.
\v 39 And he sent with them forty thousand men, and seven thousand horsemen: that they should come into the land of Juda, and should destroy it according to the word of the king.
\v 40 And they went forth with all their power, and came, and joined near to Emmaum in the champion country.
\v 41 And the merchants of the countries heard the name of them: and they took silver and gold exceeding much, and servants: and they came into the camp, to take the children of Israel for slaves, & there were added to them the army of Syria, & of the land of the strangers.
\v 42 And Judas saw, & his brethren, that the evils were multiplied, and the armies approached to their borders: and they knew the king's words, which he commanded to do to the people unto destruction and consummation:
\v 43 and they said every one to his neighbour: Let us set up the abasing of our people, & let us fight for our people, and our holies.
\v 44 And an assembly was gathered, that they should be ready unto battle: & that they should pray and desire mercy & miserations. \f + \fr 3:44 \ft Praying, fasting & other works of penance are the best armour in holy wars for religion.\f*
\v 45 And Jerusalem was not inhabited, but was a desert: there was none that came in and went out of her children: and the holy place was conculcated: and the children of strangers were in the castle, there was the inhabitation of the Gentiles, and pleasure was taken away from Jacob, & there failed their pipe and harp.
\v 46 And they gathered together, and came into Maspha against Jerusalem: because the place of prayer in Israel was in Maspha before. \f + \fr 3:46 \ft Public place of prayer was, first in Silo, Iosue. 18. after in Maspha. 1. Reg. 7. lastly in Jerusalem.\f*
\v 47 And they fasted that day, and clothed themselves with haircloths, and put ashes on their head: and they rent their garments:
\v 48 and they laid open the books of the law, out of which the Gentiles searched the similitude of their idols:
\v 49 and they brought the ornaments of Priests, and first-fruits, & tithes, & raised up Nazareites, that had fulfilled their days:
\v 50 and they cried with a loud voice to heaven, saying: What shall we do with these, & whither shall we carry them?
\v 51 And thy holies are conculcated, and they are contaminated, and thy Priests are brought into mourning, & into humiliation.
\v 52 And behold the Nations are come together against us to destroy us: thou knowest what things they intend against us.
\v 53 How shall we be able to stand before their face, unless thou o God do help us?
\v 54 And with trumpets they cried out with a loud voice.
\v 55 And after these things Judas appointed captains of the people, tribunes, and centurions, and sergeants, and decurions. \f + \fr 3:55 \ft * pentacontarchos.\f*
\v 56 And he said to them, that built houses, and despoused wives, and planted vineyards, and to the fearful, that every one should return into his house, according to the law. \x + \xo 3:56 \xt Deu. 20.\x*
\v 57 And they removed the camp, and pitched at the South of Emmaum.
\v 58 And Judas said: Gird up yourselves, and be mighty sons, and be ready against the morning, that you may fight against these nations, which are assembled against us to destroy us, and our holies,
\v 59 because it is better for us to die in battle, than to see the evils of our nation, and of the holies:
\v 60 but as it shall be the will in heaven, so be it done. \f + \fr 3:60 \ft This most godly resolution encouraged themselves, & procured God's merciful protection.\f*
\c 4
\p
\v 1 And Gorgias took five thousand men, & a thousand chosen horsemen: & they removed the camp by night, \f + \fr 4:1 \ft The third battle made by Judas was against this Gorgias, another captain of Antiochus Epiphanes.\f*
\v 2 that they might approach to the camp of the Jews, and might strike them suddenly: & the children that were of the castle, were their guides.
\v 3 And Judas heard, & arose, he and the mighties to strike the power of the king's army, that were in Emmaum. \f + \fr 4:3 \ft Vigilancy in rulers and pastors preserveth from all the devil's stratagems.\f*
\v 4 For as yet the army was dispersed from the camp.
\v 5 And Gorgias came into the camp of Judas by night, and found no man, & he sought them in the mountains: because he said: These fly from us.
\v 6 And when the day was come, Judas appeared in the field with three thousand men only, which had not harness and swords as they would:
\v 7 and they saw the camp of the Gentiles strong, and the men in brigantines, and horsemen round about them, and these were skillful to battle.
\v 8 And Judas said to the men that were with him: Fear not the multitude of them, & of their assault be not afraid. \f + \fr 4:8 \ft Confidence in God procureth his assistance.\f*
\v 9 Remember in what sort our fathers were saved in the red sea, when Pharao with a great army followed them.
\v 10 And now let us cry towards heaven: and our Lord will have mercy on us, and will be mindful of the testament of our fathers, and will destroy this army, before our face this day:
\v 11 and all Nations shall know that there is one that redeemeth and delivereth Israel.
\v 12 And the aliens lifted up their eyes, and saw them coming against them.
\v 13 And they went out of the camp into battle, and these that were with Judas, sounded with the trumpet.
\v 14 And they met together: and the Gentiles were discomfited, and fled into the plain.
\v 15 But all the hindmost fell by the sword, and they pursued them as far as Gezeron, and even to the plains of Idumea, and of Azotus, and of Jamnia: and there fell of them even to three thousand men.
\v 16 And Judas returned, and his army following him.
\v 17 And he said to the people: Covet not the spoils: because there is battle against us,
\v 18 and Gorgias & his army are near us in the mount: but stand ye now against our enemies, and overthrow them, and you shall take the spoils afterwards secure.
\v 19 And as Judas was speaking these words, lo a certain part appeared looking forth from the mountain.
\v 20 And Gorgias saw that his men were turned to flight, & that they burnt the camp: for the smoke that was seen declared what was done.
\v 21 Which things seen they feared exceedingly, beholding withal both Judas, and the army in the plain ready to battle.
\v 22 And they did all fly into the plain of the aliens:
\v 23 & Judas returned to the spoils of the camp, & they took much gold, and silver, and hyacinth, and purple of the sea, and great riches.
\v 24 And turning they sung an hymn, & blessed God towards heaven, because he is good, because his mercy is for ever. \x + \xo 4:24 \xt Psal. 106.\x*
\v 25 And great salvation was made in Israel in that day.
\v 26 And whosoever escaped of the aliens, they came and told Lysias all things that had chanced.
\v 27 Which when he heard being amazed he fainted in mind: that such things chanced not in Israel, as he would, & such as the king commanded. \f + \fr 4:27 \ft * li. 2. c. 8. v. 8. O\f*
\v 28 And the year following Lysias gathered of chosen men three score thousand, & of horsemen five thousand, to overthrow them. \f + \fr 4:28 \ft The fourth great battle of Judas was against Lysias sent by Antiochus into Jury.\f*
\v 29 And they came into Jewry, and pitched the camp in Bethoron, and Judas met them with ten thousand men.
\v 30 And they saw the army strong, and he prayed, and said: Blessed art thou o saviour of Israel, which brakest the assault of the mighty by the hand of thy servant David, & didst deliver the camp of the aliens into the hand of Jonathas Saul's son, and of his esquire. \x + \xo 4:30 \xt 1. Reg. 17. 1. Reg. 14.\x*
\v 31 shut up this army in the hand of thy people Israel, and let them be confounded in their army and horsemen.
\v 32 Give them fear, and consume the boldness of their strength, and let them be shaken with their contrition,
\v 33 cast them down with the sword of them that love thee: & let all that know thy name, praise thee in hymns.
\v 34 And they joined battle: and there fell of the army of Lysias five thousand men.
\v 35 And Lysias seeing the flight of his men, and the boldness of the Jews, & that they are ready either to live or to die manfully, he went to Antioch, and chose soldiers, that being multiplied they might come again into Jewry.
\v 36 But Judas, and his brethren said: Behold our enemies are discomfited: let us go up now to cleanse the holy places, & to renew them. \f + \fr 4:36 \ft As it was the first and chief intention of Judas to defend religion & holy things, so having expugned their enemies, his chief care is to purge the temple, and to restore all holy rites of God's true service.\f*
\v 37 And all the army assembled together, and they went up into mount Sion.
\v 38 And they saw the sanctification desert, and the altar profaned, and the gates burnt, and in the courts shrubs grown up as in a forest, or on the mountains, and the chambers thrown down.
\v 39 And they rent their garments, and lamented with a great Lamentation, and laid ashes upon their head:
\v 40 and they fell on their face upon the earth, & cried out with trumpets of significations, & cried towards heaven.
\v 41 Then Judas ordained men to fight against them that were in the castle, till they cleansed the holy places.
\v 42 And he chose Priests without spot, having their will in the law of God:
\v 43 and they cleansed the holy places, and took away the stones of contamination into an unclean place. \f + \fr 4:43 \ft Altars, temples, & statues of false gods made of stone, and set up in the temple. c. 1. v. 50. were now destroyed.\f*
\v 44 And he considered of the altar of holocausts, that was profaned, what he should do with it.
\v 45 And good counsel came to their minds, to destroy it: lest perhaps it might be a reproach to them, because the Gentiles contaminated it, and they threw it down.
\v 46 And they laid up the stones in the mount of the house in a place convenient, till their should come a Prophet, & give answer concerning them.
\v 47 And they took whole stones according to the law, and builded a new altar according to that which was before:
\v 48 and they built the holy places, and the things that were within the temple inward: and the temple, and the courts they sanctified.
\v 49 And they made the holy vessels new, and brought in the candlestick, and the altar of incenses, and the table into the temple.
\v 50 And they put incense upon the altar, and lighted the lamps, that were upon the candlestick, and they gave light in the temple.
\v 51 And they set loaves upon the table, and hung up the veils, and finished all the works, that they had made.
\v 52 And before the morning they arose the five and twentieth day of the ninth month (this is the month of Casleu) of the hundreth & eight and fortieth year: \f + \fr 4:52 \ft The temple was purged two years & something more after the profanation, which was in the year 145. ch. 1. v. 57.\f*
\v 53 and they offered sacrifice according to the law upon the new altar of holocausts, which they made.
\v 54 According to the time and according to the day, wherein the heathen contaminated it, in the same was it renewed in canticles, & harps, and lutes, and in cymbals.
\v 55 And all the people fell on their face, and they adored toward heaven, and blessed him that prospered them.
\v 56 And they made the dedication of the altar eight days, and they offered holocausts with joy, and sacrifice of salvation, and of praise. \f + \fr 4:56 \ft Our Saviour observed this feast being instituted long after the Law of Moyses. Ioan. 10. v. 22.\f* \x + \xo 4:56 \xt Ioan. 10.\x*
\v 57 And they adorned the face of the temple with gold crowns, and little shields: & they dedicated the gates, and the chambers, and hanged doors upon them.
\v 58 And there was made exceeding great joy in the people, and the reproach of the Gentiles was turned away.
\v 59 And Judas decreed, and his brethren, and all the Church of Israel, that the day of the dedication of the altar be kept in the times thereof from year to year for eight days, from the five & twentieth day of the month Casleu, with joy and gladness.
\v 60 And they builded at that time mount Sion, and round about high walls, and strong towers, lest sometime the Gentiles should come, and conculcate it as they did before.
\v 61 And he placed an army there, to keep it, & he fenced it to keep Bethsura, that the people might have a munition against the face of Idumea. \f + \fr 4:61 \ft * li. 2. c. 10. v. 1.\f*
\c 5
\p
\v 1 And it came to pass, as the Gentiles round about heard that the altar was builded up, and the sanctuary as before, they were exceeding angry: \f + \fr 5:1 \ft In this chapter is mention of ten battles in which Judas or his brethren Jonathas and Simon were victors.\f* \f + \fr 5:1 \ft Q\f*
\v 2 and they thought to take away the stock of Jacob, that were among them, and they began to kill of the people, and to persecute.
\v 3 And Judas fought against the children of Esau in Idumea, & them that were in Acrabathane: because they beset the Israelites round about, and he struck them with a great plague. \f + \fr 5:3 \ft The first against the Idumeans in Acrabathane.\f*
\v 4 And he remembered the malice of the children of Bean, which were to the people a snare and a scandal, lying in wait for them in the way. \f + \fr 5:4 \ft The second against the Beanites.\f*
\v 5 And they were shut up by him in towers, and he came near to them, and anathematized them, and burnt their towers with fire, with all that were in them. \f + \fr 5:5 \ft utterly destroyed.\f*
\v 6 And he passed to the children of Ammon, and found a strong band, and a copious people, and Timothee their captain: \f + \fr 5:6 \ft The third against the Ammonites.\f*
\v 7 and he made many battles with them, and they were discomfited in their sight, & he struck them:
\v 8 and he took Gazer the city, and her daughters, and returned into Jewry. \f + \fr 5:8 \ft villages.\f*
\v 9 And the Gentiles that are in Galaad, gathered together against the Israelites, that were in their coasts to dispatch them: and they fled into the fortress of Datheman. \f + \fr 5:9 \ft The fourth against the Galadites.\f*
\v 10 And they sent letters to Judas, and his brethren, saying: The heathen round about are gathered together against us, to dispatch us:
\v 11 and they prepare to come, and to occupy the fortress into which we are fled: and Timothee is the captain of their host.
\v 12 Now therefore come, & deliver us, out of their hands, because a multitude of us is fallen.
\v 13 And all our brethren, that were in the places of Tubin, are slain: and they led away their wives captives, and the children, and the spoils, and they have slain there almost a thousand men.
\v 14 And the epistles were yet in reading, and lo other messengers came out of Galilee their coats rent, reporting according to these words:
\v 15 saying that there were assembled against them from Ptolemais, and Tyre, and Sidon, and all Galilee is replenished with aliens, to consume us.
\v 16 And as Judas and the people heard these words, a great assembly assembled together to consider what they should do for their brethren, that were in tribulation, and were expugned of them.
\v 17 And Judas said to Simon his brother: Choose thee men, and go, and deliver thy brethren in Galilee: and I, and my brother Jonathas will go into the country of Galaad. \f + \fr 5:17 \ft The fifth against the Galileans of the Gentiles.\f*
\v 18 And he left Joseph the son of Zacharie, and Azarias, captains of the people with the residue of the army in Jurie to keep it:
\v 19 and he commanded them, saying: Be ye over this people: & make no battle against the heathen, till we return.
\v 20 And there were parted to Simon three thousand men, to go into Galilee: but to Judas eight thousand to go into the country of Galaad.
\v 21 And Simon went into Galilee, & made many battles with the heathen: and the heathen were discomfited before his face, and he pursued them even to the gate of Ptolemais.
\v 22 And there fell of the heathen almost three thousand men, & he took the spoils of them,
\v 23 and he took them that were in Galilee & in Arbatis with their wives, and children, & all things that they had, and he brought them into Jurie with great joy.
\v 24 And Judas Machabeus, and Jonathas his brother passed over Jordan, and went three days' journey through the desert.
\v 25 And the Nabutheians met them, & received them peaceably, & told them all things, that had happened to their brethren in the country of Galaad,
\v 26 and that many of them were comprehended in Barasa, and Bosor, and in Alimis, and in Casphor, & Mageth, & Carnaim, all these cities fenced, & great.
\v 27 Yea and in the rest of the cities of Galaad they are held captive, & on the morrow they appointed to remove the army near to these cities, and to take them, & to dispatch them in one day.
\v 28 And Judas turned & his army the way into Bosor suddenly, and took the city: and he slew every male in the edge of the sword, & took all their spoils, & burnt it with fire.
\v 29 And they arose thence by night, & went even to the fortress.
\v 30 And it came to pass early in the morning, when they had lifted up their eyes, & behold much people, whereof there was no number, carrying ladders, & engines to take the fortress, and they expugned them.
\v 31 And Judas saw that the battle began, and the cry of the battle ascended to heaven as a trumpet, and a great cry out of the city:
\v 32 & he said to his host: Fight ye today for your brethren.
\v 33 And he came with three ranks behind them & they cried out with trumpets, & cried in prayer.
\v 34 And the camp of Timothee understood that it was Machabeus, and they fled back from his presence: and they struck them with a great plague: and there fell of them in that day almost eight thousand men.
\v 35 And Judas turned aside into Maspha, and expugned, & took it, and he slew every male thereof, & he took the spoils thereof, & burnt it with fire.
\v 36 From thence he marched, and took Casbon, and Mageth, and Bosor, & the rest of the cities of Galaad.
\v 37 But after these words Timothee gathered another army, and camped against Raphon beyond the torrent.
\v 38 And Judas send to view the army: and they reported unto him, saying: That all nations, that are round about us, are assembled against us, an army exceeding great:
\v 39 and they have hired the Arabians to help them, & they have camped beyond the torrent, being ready to come unto thee into battle. And Judas went to meet them.
\v 40 And Timothee said to the princes of his army: When Judas shall approach, & his army to the torrent of water: if he pass over unto us first, we shall not be able to sustain him: because prevailing he will prevail against us.
\v 41 But if he be afraid to pass over, and camp without the river, let us pass over to them, and we shall prevail against them.
\v 42 But as Judas approached to the torrent of water, he set the scribes of the people by the torrent, & commanded them, saying: Leave not a man: but let all come into the battle.
\v 43 And he passed over to them first, & all the people after him, & all the heathen were discomfited at their presence, & they threw away their weapons, & fled to the temple, that was in Carnaim.
\v 44 And he took the city it-self, & the temple he burnt with fire, with all things that were therein: & Carnaim was subdued, & could not stand against the face of Judas. \f + \fr 5:44 \ft The sixth against the Carnaimites.\f*
\v 45 And Judas gathered together all the Israelites, that were in the country of Galaad, from the least even to the greatest, and their wives, and children, and an army exceeding great, to come into the land of Juda.
\v 46 And they came as far as Ephron: and this city was great, situate in the entrance, fenced exceedingly, and there was no means to decline from it on the right hand or on the left, but the way was through the midst. \f + \fr 5:46 \ft The seventh against the Ephronites.\f*
\v 47 And they that were in the city, shut in themselves, and stopped the gates with stones: & Judas sent to them in peaceable words,
\v 48 saying: Let us pass through your land, and go into our country: and no man shall hurt you, only on foot we will pass. And they would not open unto them. \x + \xo 5:48 \xt Num. 20.\x*
\v 49 And Judas commanded proclamation to be made in the camp, that they should approach every man in the place, wherein he was.
\v 50 and the men of strength approached, and he assaulted that city all the day, and all the night, and the city was delivered into his hand:
\v 51 & they slew every male in the edge of the sword, and he rooted it up, and took the spoils thereof, & passed through all the city upon the slain.
\v 52 And they passed over Jordan in the great plain, against the face of Bethsan.
\v 53 And Judas gathered together the hindmost, & he exhorted the people throughout all the way, till they came into the land of Juda: \f + \fr 5:53 \ft Agood and pious captain cherisheth and comforteth the weak soldiers:\f* \f + \fr 5:53 \ft and encouraged all to shew their fortitude.\f*
\v 54 and they went up into mount Sion with joy and gladness, and offered holocausts because none of them was fallen till they returned in peace.
\v 55 And in the days that Judas & Jonathas were in the land of Galaad, & Simon his brother in Galilee against the face of Ptolomais,
\v 56 Joseph the son of Zacharie heard, & Azarias, the princes of the band, the things well achieved, and the battles that were made, \f + \fr 5:56 \ft Men that presume of their own strength without commission from lawful authority have not God's assistance, and so fail in their attempts, as not called of God amongst those men, by whom salvation is made in Israel. v. 62.\f*
\v 57 and he said: Let us also make us a name, and let us go fight against the heathen, that are round about us.
\v 58 And he commanded them that were in his army, and they went to Jamnia.
\v 59 And Gorgias went forth out of the city, and his men to meet them into battle.
\v 60 And Joseph and Azarias were chased in flight even unto the borders of Jurie: and there fell that day of the people of Israel about two thousand men, and there was made a great tumult in the people:
\v 61 because they heard not Judas, & his brethren, thinking that they should do manfully.
\v 62 But they were not of the seed of those men by whom salvation was made in Israel.
\v 63 And the men of Juda were magnified exceedingly in the sight of all Israel, and of all nations where their name was heard.
\v 64 And they came together unto them, with acclamations for their good success.
\v 65 And Judas went out, and his brethren, and they expugned the children of Esau in the land, that is toward the South, and they struck Chebron, and her daughters: and the walls thereof and the towers he burnt with fire round about. \f + \fr 5:65 \ft The eighth against the Idumeans, in Chebron.\f*
\v 66 And he removed the camp to go into the land of the aliens, and he walked through Samaria. \f + \fr 5:66 \ft The ninth against the Samaritanes.\f*
\v 67 In that day fell the Priests in battle, whilst they will do manfully, whilst they go forth without counsel into battle.
\v 68 And Judas declined to Azotus into the land of the aliens, and he threw down their altars, and the sculptiles of their gods he burnt with fire: and he took the spoils of the cities, and returned into the land of Juda. \f + \fr 5:68 \ft The tenth against the Philistiims in Azotus.\f*
\c 6
\p
\v 1 And king Antiochus walked through the higher countries, and he heard that there was a city Elymais in Persis, most noble, and plentiful in silver & gold, \f + \fr 6:1 \ft The full history of Antiochus Epiphanes his death is written in this chapter to the 16. v. and in all the 9. of the second Book.\f*
\v 2 and a temple therein exceeding rich: and coverings thereof gold, and brigantines, and shields, which Alexander Philip's son the king of Macedonia that reigned first in Greece left there.
\v 3 And he came, and sought to take the city, and to spoil it, and he could not, because the word was known to them that were in the city.
\v 4 And they rose up into battle, and he fled from thence, and departed with great sorrow, and returned into Babylonia. \f + \fr 6:4 \ft Finally he returned into the country of Babylon:\f*
\v 5 And there came one that told him in Persis, that the camps that were in the land of Juda, were put to flight: \f + \fr 6:5 \ft but before he arrived there he heard the bad news of his army in Jury, & fell into intolerable and desperate diseases, v. 8. and li. 2. ch. 9. v. 5.\f*
\v 6 and that Lysias went with great power with the first, and was put to flight before the face of the Jews, and they grew strong with armour, and force, and many spoils: which they took out of the camps, which they destroyed:
\v 7 and that they threw down the abomination which they had builded upon the altar that was in Jerusalem, and the sanctification they compassed about as before with high walls, yea and Bethsura his city,
\v 8 And it came to pass as the king heard these words, he was sore afraid, and was moved exceedingly: and he lay down upon his bed, and fell into sickness for sorrow, because it was not chanced to him as he thought.
\v 9 And he was there for many days: because there was renewed in him great sorrowfulness, and he made account to die.
\v 10 And he called all his friends, & said to them: sleep is departed from mine eyes, and I am fallen away, and my heart is gone for pensiveness:
\v 11 and I said in my heart: Into how great tribulation am I come, & into what waves of sorrow, wherein now I am: who was pleasant, and beloved in my power!
\v 12 But now I remember the evils, that I have done in Jerusalem, from whence also I took away all the spoils of gold, and of silver, that were in it, and I sent to take away the inhabitants of Jewry, without cause. \f + \fr 6:12 \ft All this was but feigned repentance. li. 2. ch. 9. v. 13.\f*
\v 13 I know therefore that for this cause have these evils found me: and lo I perish with great sorrow in a strange country.
\v 14 And he called Philip, one of his friends, & he made him chief over all his kingdom.
\v 15 And he gave him the crown, and his robe, and ring, that he should bring Antiochus his son, and should bring him up to reign.
\v 16 And Antiochus the king died there in the year an hundreth forty nine. \f + \fr 6:16 \ft Antiochus began to persecute the Jews in the year 143. ch. 1. v. 21. and dying this year, 149. it appeareth that his persecution dured about six years, or somewhat more: agreeable to the answer of the Angel Dan. 8. v. 14. that it should endure 2300. days, which make six years, & almost four months. Within which time Judas by his valor obtained & purged the holy places, in the year 148. ch. 6. v. 52. some months before Antiochus' death.\f* \f + \fr 6:16 \ft * li. 2. c. 9. v. 1. S\f*
\v 17 And Lysias understood that the king was dead, and he appointed Antiochus his son to reign, who he brought up a young man: and he called his name Eupator. \f + \fr 6:17 \ft * li. 2. c. 10. v. 10. V\f*
\v 18 And they that were in the castle, had inclosed Israel round about the holy places: and they sought them evils always, and the strengthening of the Gentiles.
\v 19 And Judas thought to destroy them: and he called together all the people, to besiege them.
\v 20 And they came together, and besieged them in the year an hundredth fifty, and they made balists and engines.
\v 21 And certain of them that were besieged, went forth: and some impious men of Israel joined themselves unto them,
\v 22 and they went to the king, & said: How long doest thou not judgements, & revengest our brethren?
\v 23 We decreed to serve thy father, and to walk in his precepts, and obey his edicts:
\v 24 and the children of our people for this alienated themselves from us, & whosoever were found of us, they were slain, and our inheritances were spoiled.
\v 25 And not to us only have they extended the hand, but also into all our coasts.
\v 26 and behold they have approached this day to the castle in Jerusalem to take it, and they have fortified a fortress in Bethsura:
\v 27 and unless thou prevent them more speedily, they will do greater things than these, and thou shalt not be able to win them.
\v 28 And the king was angry, as he heard these things: & he called together all his friends, & the princes of his army, and them that were over the horsemen.
\v 29 Yea and of other realms, and of the islands by the sea there came unto him hired armies.
\v 30 And the number of his army was an hundred thousand footmen, and twenty thousand horsemen, and elephants thirty two, taught to battle.
\v 31 And they came through Idumea, and approached to Bethsura, and fought many days, and they made engines and came forth, and burnt them with fire, and fought manfully.
\v 32 And Judas departed from the castle, & removed the camp to Bethzacaram against the king's camp.
\v 33 And the king arose before it was light, and stirred the bands into fierceness against the way to Bethzacaram: and the armies made themselves ready to the battle, and they sounded with trumpets:
\v 34 and to the elephants they shewed the blood of the grape, and of the mulberry, to provoke them to the battle. \f + \fr 6:34 \ft Blood of the grape (wine Deut. 32. v. 14. ) and juice of mulberries do incite elephants to fight. As some kind of blood or smell thereof doth incite hounds to hunt. Vallesius c. 82. sacræ Philosophiæ.\f*
\v 35 And they divided the beasts by the legions: & there stood by every elephant a thousand men in coats of mail, and helmets of brass on their heads: and five hundred horsemen set in order were chosen for every beast.
\v 36 These before the time wheresoever the beast was, there were they: & whither soever it went, they went, & they departed not from it.
\v 37 Yea and upon them were strong wooden towers protecting every beast: and upon them engines, and upon every one thirty two men of strength which fought from above: and within the master of the beast.
\v 38 And the residue of the horsemen he placed on this side and on that side into two parts, with trumpets to stir up the army, and to urge them that stood thick together in the legions thereof.
\v 39 And as the sun did shine upon the bucklers of gold, and of brass, the mountains glistered therewith, & they glistered as lamps of fire.
\v 40 And part of the king's army was severed by the high mountains, & another part by the low places: & they marched warily and orderly.
\v 41 And all the inhabitants of the land were moved at the voice of the multitude of them, and the marching of the troop, and the rattling of the armour, for it was an army exceeding great and strong.
\v 42 And Judas approached, and his army into battle: and there fell of the king's army six hundred men.
\v 43 And Eleazar the son of Saura saw one of the beasts harnessed with the king's harness: & it was eminent above the other beasts; & it seemed to him that the king was on it:
\v 44 and he gave himself to deliver his people, and to get himself an everlasting name.
\v 45 And he ran to it boldly in the midst of the legion, killing on the right hand, & on the left, and they were slain of him on this side and that side.
\v 46 And he went under the feet of the elephant, and put himself under him, and slew him: and it fell to the ground upon him, and he died there. \f + \fr 6:46 \ft S. Ambrose li. 1. c. 40. Offic. highly commendeth the fortitude of this soldier, putting himself in so present danger of death, fighting for religion.\f*
\v 47 And they seeing the king's power, and the fierceness of his army, turned themselves aside from them.
\v 48 But the king's camp went up against them unto Jerusalem: and the king's camp approached to Jurie and mount Sion.
\v 49 And he made peace with them that were in Bethsura: & they came forth out of the city, because there were no victuals for them there being shut up, because it was the sabbaths of the land.
\v 50 And the king took Bethsura: and he placed there a garrison to keep it.
\v 51 And he turned the place of the sanctification many days: and he placed there arbalists, and engines, and instruments to cast fire, & pieces to cast stones, and arrows, & scorpions to shoot arrows, and slings.
\v 52 And they also made engines against their engines, and they fought many days.
\v 53 But there were no victuals in the city, for that it was the seventh year: and they that had remained in Jury of the Gentiles, had consumed their remains, that had been laid up.
\v 54 And there remained in the holies few men, because famine had prevailed over them: and they were dispersed every man into his place.
\v 55 And Lysias heard that Philip, whom king Antiochus when he lived, had appointed to bring up his son to reign,
\v 56 was returned from Persis, and Media, and the army that went with him, and that he sought to take upon him the affairs of the kingdom:
\v 57 and he hastened to go, and to say to the king, & to the princes of the army: We decay daily, and there is little victual for us, and the place that we besiege, is fenced, and it lieth upon us to take order for the kingdom.
\v 58 Now therefore let us give the right hands to these men, and make peace with them, and with all their nation.
\v 59 And let us decree for them, that they walk in their own ordinances as before. For, because of their ordinances which we despised, they have been wrath, and have done all these things.
\v 60 And the word was liked in the sight of the king, and of the princes: and he sent unto them to make peace: and they received it.
\v 61 And the king and the princes sware to them: & they came out of the fortress.
\v 62 And the king entered mount Sion, and saw the munition of the place: and he brake quickly the oath which he sware, and commanded to destroy the wall round about.
\v 63 And he departed in haste, and returned to Antioch, and found Philip ruling over the city: and he fought against him and won the city. \f + \fr 6:63 \ft * li. 2. c. 13. v. 1.\f*
\c 7
\p
\v 1 In the year an hundreth fifty first went forth Demetrius the son of Seleucus from the city of Rome, and he ascended with few men into a city by the sea side, & reigned there. \f + \fr 7:1 \ft This Seleucus was brother to Antiochus Epiphanes: & so Antiochus Eupator was Demetrius his cousin-german.\f* \f + \fr 7:1 \ft X\f*
\v 2 And it came to pass, as he entered into the house of the kingdom of his fathers, the army took Antiochus, and Lysias, to bring them unto him.
\v 3 And the king was known to him: & he said: Shew me not their face.
\v 4 And the army slew them. And Demetrius sat upon the seat of his kingdom:
\v 5 and there came to him the wicked and impious men of Israel: and Alcimus the captain of them, who would be made the Priest. \f + \fr 7:5 \ft Alcimus was now in place of the high-priest, as Menelaus had been before him, set up by Antiochus: & therefore is rightly here said: he would have been the chief Priest, but indeed was not. For the true high-priesthood was amongst the Machabees.\f*
\v 6 And they accused the people to the king, saying: Judas and his brethren have destroyed all thy friends, & us he hath destroyed out of our land. \f + \fr 7:6 \ft This usurper with his complices devised false accusations against Judas and the rest, to incense the King against them. And by great gifts gained the king's favour. li. 2. c. 14. v. 4.\f*
\v 7 Now therefore send a man, whom thou doest credit, that he may go, and see all the destruction, that he hath done to us, and to the king's countries: and let him punish all his friends, & their aiders.
\v 8 And the king chose of his friends Bacchides, that ruled beyond the great river in the kingdom, and was faithful to the king: & he sent him,
\v 9 to see the destruction that Judas hath made: and Alcimus the impious man he appointed to the Priesthood, and gave him in commandment to make revenge upon the children of Israel.
\v 10 And they arose, and came with a great army into the land of Juda: and they sent messengers, and spake to Judas, and his brethren with peaceable words in guile.
\v 11 And they attended not to their words: for they saw that they came with a great army.
\v 12 And there assembled to Alcimus and Bacchides a congregation of the scribes to require the things that are just:
\v 13 and first, the Assideans that were in the children of Israel, and they sought peace of them. \f + \fr 7:13 \ft Among the Scribes the Assideans were first consulted, being as learned as the Pharisees, or any other, and indeed more sincere, as we noted ch. 2. v. 42.\f*
\v 14 for they said: A man that is a Priest of the seed of Aaron is come, he will not deceive us. \f + \fr 7:14 \ft And so Alcimus deceiving them in a matter of fact, to wit, that himself meant truly (as he did not) cruelly murdered three score of them.\f*
\v 15 And he spake with them peaceable words: and he sware to them, saying: We will do you no harm, nor your friends.
\v 16 And they believed him. And he took of them threescore men, & slew them in one day, according to the word that is written:
\v 17 The flesh of thy saints, and the blood of them they have shed round about Jerusalem, and there was none to bury them. \x + \xo 7:17 \xt Psal. 78.\x*
\v 18 And there fell fear, and trembling upon all the people, because they said: There is no truth and judgement in them: for they have transgressed the appointment & the oath which they sware.
\v 19 And Bacchides removed the camp from Jerusalem, and approached to Bethzecha: and he sent, and took many of them that were fled from him, and certain of the people he killed, & threw them into a great pit.
\v 20 And he committed the country to Alcimus, and left with him aid to help him. And Bacchides went away to the king:
\v 21 & Alcimus did what he could for the principality of his Priesthood:
\v 22 and there gathered together unto him all that disturbed their people, & they obtained the land of Juda, & made a great plague in Israel.
\v 23 And Judas saw all the evils that Alcimus did, and they that were with him, to the children of Israel, much more than the Gentiles.
\v 24 And he went out into all the coasts of Jurie round about, & did vengeance upon the men that revolted, & they ceased to go forth any more into the country.
\v 25 But Alcimus saw that Judas prevailed, & they that were with him: & he knew that he could not stand with them, and he went back to the king, & accused them of many crimes. \f + \fr 7:25 \ft * li. 2. c. 14. v. 1. Z\f*
\v 26 And the king sent Nicanor, one of his nobler princes: that practised enmities against Israel: and he commanded him to destroy the people. \f + \fr 7:26 \ft This Nicanor was the most terrible enemy against Judas, but was at last slain by him. v. 43. & li. 2. c. 15. v. 28.\f*
\v 27 And Nicanor came into Jerusalem with a great army, and he sent to Judas & to his brethren in peaceable words with guile,
\v 28 saying: Let there be no fighting between me and you: I will come with few men, to see your faces with peace.
\v 29 And he came to Judas, & they saluted one another peaceably: & the enemies were ready to catch Judas.
\v 30 And the thing was known to Judas that he was come with guile: and he was sore afraid of him, and would not see his face any more.
\v 31 And Nicanor knew that his counsel was disclosed: and he went forth to Judas into battle beside Capharsalama.
\v 32 And there fell of Nicanor's army almost five thousand men, & they fled into the city of David.
\v 33 And after these words Nicanor went up into mount Sion: and there went forth of the Priests of the people to salute him in peace, and to shew him the holocausts, that were offered for the king.
\v 34 And scorning he contemned them, & polluted them: and he spake proudly,
\v 35 and sware with anger, saying: Unless Judas be delivered, & his army into my hands, incontinent when I shall return in peace I will burn this house. And he went out with great anger:
\v 36 and the Priests entered in, and stood before the face of the altar and the temple: and weeping they said:
\v 37 Thou o Lord hast chosen this house for thy name to be invocated therein, that it might be a house of prayer, and obsecration for thy people.
\v 38 Take vengeance upon this man, and his army, and let them fall by the sword: remember their blasphemies, and grant not unto them to be permanent. \f + \fr 7:38 \ft * li. 2. c. 14. v. 12. B\f*
\v 39 And Nicanor went out from Jerusalem, & moved the camp, near to Bethhoron: and the army of Syria met him. \f + \fr 7:39 \ft This was the last conflict between Judas and Nicanor written more largely in the last chapter of the second book.\f*
\v 40 And Judas approached in Adarsa with three thousand men: and Judas prayed, and said:
\v 41 They that were sent by king Sennacherib, o Lord, because they blasphemed thee, an angel came forth, and struck of them an hundred eighty five thousand: \x + \xo 7:41 \xt 4. Reg. 19.\x*
\v 42 so destroy this army in our sight today, and let the rest know that he hath spoken it upon the holy places: and judge thou him according to his malice.
\v 43 And the armies joined battle the thirteenth day of the month Adar: and the camp of Nicanor was discomfited, & himself was slain first in the battle.
\v 44 And as his army saw that Nicanor was slain, they threw away their weapons, & fled:
\v 45 and they pursued them one day's journey from Adazer, even till ye come into Gazara, & with trumpets they sounded after them with significations.
\v 46 And they went forth out of all the towns of Jurie round about, and they pushed them with the horns, and they turned again to them, and they were all slain with the sword, and there was not left of them so much as one.
\v 47 And they took the spoils of them for a prey: and Nicanor's head they cut off, and his right hand, which he had proudly stretched forth, & they brought it, & hung it up against Jerusalem.
\v 48 And the people rejoiced exceedingly, & they spent that day in great gladness.
\v 49 And he ordained that this day should be kept every year the thirteenth of the month Adar.
\v 50 And the land of Juda was quiet for a few days. \f + \fr 7:50 \ft Whiles Judas disposed things pertaining to religion, and the commonwealth: Demetrius prepared for wars. ch. 9. v. 3.\f* \f + \fr 7:50 \ft l. 2. c. 15. v. 1.\f*
\c 8
\p
\v 1 And Judas heard of the name of the Romans, that they are mighty of power, and agree unto all things that are requested of them: and whosoever have come unto them, they have made amity with them, and that they are mighty of power. \f + \fr 8:1 \ft Of the renowned acts of the Romans, other Historiographers have also written largely: especially Livius, Diodorus, Iustinus, Florus, Varre, Plutarchus, and many others.\f* \f + \fr 8:1 \ft D\f*
\v 2 And they heard of their battles, and goodly acts, which they did in Galatia, that they overcame them, and brought them under tribute:
\v 3 and how great things they did in the country of Spain, & that they brought into their power the metals of silver and gold, that are there, and possessed every place by their counsel and patience:
\v 4 and destroyed the places that were very far off from them, and the kings that came upon them from the ends of the earth, and struck them with a great plague: and the rest give them tribute every year. \f + \fr 8:4 \ft What places these were Iosephus expresseth. l. 12. c. 17.\f*
\v 5 And Philip and Perses the king of the Ceteans, & the rest that had borne weapon against them, they discomfited in battle, and overcame them:
\v 6 and that Antiochus the great king of Asia, who made battle against them, having an hundred and twenty elephants, and horsemen, and chariots and army exceeding great was discomfited by them: \f + \fr 8:6 \ft Polybius li. 5. writeth that Antiochus had 102. elephants in his war against Ptolemeus, & therefore it is not to be marveled that he had 120. against the Romans.\f*
\v 7 and that they took him alive, and appointed him that himself and they that should reign after him, should give a great tribute, and he should give hostages, and the thing appointed him.
\v 8 and the region of the Indes, and the Medes, and the Lydians of their best countries: and the same being taken of them, they gave to Eumenes the king.
\v 9 And that they which were in Hellada, would have gone to dispatch them: and the word was known to them,
\v 10 and they sent unto them one captain, and they fought against them, and many of them were slain, and they led away their wives captive, and their children, and spoiled them, and possessed their land, and destroyed their walls, and brought them into bondage even until this day:
\v 11 and the residue of kingdoms, and isles that some time had resisted them, they spoiled, and brought under their power.
\v 12 But with their friends, and those that rested in them, they kept amity, and obtained the kingdoms, that were next, and that were far off: that whosoever heard their name, feared them.
\v 13 But such as they would help to reign, those reigned: and whom they would, they deposed from the kingdom: and they were exalted exceedingly.
\v 14 And in all these none bare a crown, nor was clothed with purple, to be magnified therein.
\v 15 And that they made themselves a court, and consulted daily three hundred and twenty, that sat in counsel always for the multitude, that they might do the things that were convenient:
\v 16 and they commit their government to one man every year to rule over all their land, and all they obey one, and there is no envy, nor emulation amongst them. \f + \fr 8:16 \ft Though Rome was then governed by two consuls: Yet one only ruled every day in their course, not both in one day, for so saith Livius (li. 2. hist.) it should have been more terror of two rulers, than before it had been of one king.\f*
\v 17 And Judas chose Eupolemus the son of John, the son of Jacob, and Jason the son of Eleazar, & he sent them to Rome to make amity and society with them:
\v 18 and that they should take from them the yoke of the Greeks, because they saw that they pressed the kingdom of Israel unto bondage.
\v 19 And they went to Rome, a way exceeding great, and they entered into the court, and said:
\v 20 Judas Machabeus, and his brethren, and the people of the Jews have sent us unto you to make society and peace with you, and to write us your fellows and friends.
\v 21 And the word was liked in their sight.
\v 22 And this is the rescript that they wrote again in tables of brass, and sent into Jerusalem, that it might be with them there a memorial of peace and society.
\v 23 BE IT \sc Well to The Romans\sc*, and to the nation of the Jews by sea, and by land for ever: and sword and enemy be far from them.
\v 24 But and if war be toward the Romans first, or all their fellows in all their dominion:
\v 25 the nation of the Jews shall give aid, according as the time shall appoint, with full heart:
\v 26 and to them fighting, they shall not give nor allow wheat, armour, money, ships, as it hath pleased the Romans: & they shall keep their charge, taking nothing of them.
\v 27 In like manner also & if war shall happen first to the nation of the Jews, the Romans shall help with all their heart, according as the time shall permit them:
\v 28 & to them helping shall not be given wheat, armour, money, ships, as it hath pleased the Romans: and they shall keep their charge without guile.
\v 29 According to these words did the Romans agree to the people of the Jews.
\v 30 And if after these words these or they will add to these, or take away any thing, they shall do it at their pleasure: and whatsoever they shall add, or take away, shall be ratified.
\v 31 Yea and concerning the evils, that Demetrius the king hath done against them, we have written to him, saying: Why hast thou aggravated the yoke upon our friends and fellows the Jews?
\v 32 If therefore they come again unto us against thee, we will do judgement for them, and will fight with thee by sea and land.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 In the mean time as Demetrius heard that Nicanor was fallen and his army in the battle, he added to send Bacchides and Alcimus again into Jurie, and the right wing with them. \f + \fr 9:1 \ft This happened about a year after the death of Nicanor. ch. 7. v. 50. li. 2. c. 15. 38.\f*
\v 2 And they went the way, that leadeth into Galgal, and camped in Masaloth, which is in Arbellis: and they won it, and slew of men many souls.
\v 3 In the first month of the year an hundreth and fifty two they brought the army near to Jerusalem:
\v 4 and they arose, and went into Beræa twenty thousand men, and two thousand horsemen.
\v 5 And Judas had camped in Laisa, and three thousand chosen men with him:
\v 6 and they saw the multitude of the army that they were many, and they feared exceedingly: and many withdrew themselves out of the camp, and there remained of them but eight hundred men.
\v 7 And Judas saw that his army shrunk away, and the battle pressed upon him, and his heart was broken: because he had not time to gather them together, and he was discouraged. \f + \fr 9:7 \ft Strongest men are not free from first motions of perturbation, but reflecting upon their own infirmity, & confiding in God's providence, take courage in a good cause, being assured either of temporal victory, or of eternal glory. As now it happened to this most glorious Champion. v. 18.\f*
\v 8 And he said to them that were remaining: Let us rise, and go to our adversaries, if we may be able to fight against them.
\v 9 And they dissuaded him saying: We are not able, but let us save our lives now, and return to our brethren, and then we will fight against them: and we are few.
\v 10 And Judas said: God forbid we should do this thing, to fly from them: & if our time be near, let us die manfully for our brethren, and let us not stain our glory.
\v 11 And the army moved out of the camp, and they stood to meet them: and the horsemen were divided into two parts, and the slingers, and the archers went before the army, & of the forward all mighty.
\v 12 And Bacchides was in the right wing, and the legion approached on two sides, & they sounded with trumpets:
\v 13 and they also cried out that were on Judas' side, even they also, & the earth was moved at the voice of the armies: and the battle was fought from morning even until the evening.
\v 14 And Judas saw that the stronger part of the army was on the right hand, and all the stout of heart came together with him:
\v 15 and the right side was discomfited of them, & he pursued them even to the mount of Azotus.
\v 16 And they that were in the left wing, saw that the ring wing was discomfited, and they followed after Judas, and them that were with him at the back:
\v 17 and the battle grew sore, and there fell many wounded of these and of them.
\v 18 And Judas was slain, and the rest fled.
\v 19 And Jonathas and Simon took Judas their brother, and buried him in the sepulchre of their fathers in the city Modin.
\v 20 And all the people of Israel lamented him with great lamentation, and they mourned many days,
\v 21 and said: How is the mighty fallen, that saved the people of Israel! \f + \fr 9:21 \ft The mighty may fall in the sight of men, but Judas his fortitude proved & confirmed by former heroical acts, with prosperous success, was now perfectly consummate by this most glorious end. S. Ambr. li. 1. c. 41. Offic.\f*
\v 22 And the rest of the words of Judas' battles, and of the valiant acts that he did, and of his greatness are not described: for they were exceeding many.
\v 23 And it came to pass: after the death of Judas, there came forth the wicked men in all the coasts of Israel, & there arose all that wrought iniquity. \f + \fr 9:23 \ft Where there is no governor the people shall fall. Pro. 11.\f*
\v 24 In those days was made an exceeding great famine, and all their country with themselves yielded to Bacchides.
\v 25 And Bacchides chose the impious men, & appointed them lords of the country:
\v 26 and they sought out, & searched for the friends of Judas, & brought them to Bacchides, and he took revenge on them, and scorned them.
\v 27 And there was made great tribulation in Israel, such as was not since the day, that there was no Prophet seen in Israel.
\v 28 And all the friends of Judas gathered, & said to Jonathas: \f + \fr 9:28 \ft Ionathas the third general captain of the Machabees was also high Priest after the death of Judas. Though Alcimus by the King's favour unjustly usurped the office: (ch. 7. v. 5.) whiles Judas yet lived, and until this time. v. 54.\f*
\v 29 Since thy brother Judas died, there is not a man like unto him, to go forth against the enemies, Bacchides, & them that are the enemies of our nation.
\v 30 Now therefore thee have we chosen this day to be for him our prince, and captain to wage our battle.
\v 31 And Jonathas took upon him at that time the princedom, & arose in the place of Judas his brother.
\v 32 And Bacchides understood it, and sought to kill him.
\v 33 And Jonathas understood it, and Simon his brother, and all that were with them: and they fled into the desert of Thecua, and they pitched by the water of the lake Asphar.
\v 34 And Bacchides understood it, and in the day of the Sabbaths came himself, and all his army over Jordan.
\v 35 And Jonathas sent his brother captain of the people, to desire the Nabutheians his friends, that they would lend him their provision, which was copious.
\v 36 And the children of Jambri issued forth of Madaba, and took John, & all things that he had, and went away having them. \f + \fr 9:36 \ft They also killed him. v. 38. 42.\f*
\v 37 After these words, it was told Jonathas and Simon his brother, that the children of Jambri make a great marriage, & bring the bride out of Madaba, the daughter of one of the great princes of Chanaan with great pomp.
\v 38 And they remembered the blood of John their brother: and they went up, and hid themselves under the covert of the mountain.
\v 39 And they lifted up their eyes, and saw: and lo a tumult, a great preparation: and the bridegroom came forth, and his friends, and his brethren to meet them with timbrels, and musical instruments, and many weapons.
\v 40 And they rose upon them out of the embushment, and slew them, and there fell many wounded, & the rest fled into the mountains, and they took all the spoils of them:
\v 41 and the marriage was turned into mourning, and the voice of their musical instruments into lamentation.
\v 42 And they took revenge of the blood of their brother: and they returned to the bank of Jordan. \f + \fr 9:42 \ft To revenge or punish faults in due measure, & other right circumstances, is a special virtue, moderating man's defence of his person, honour, or right, without cruelty, or remissness: and so the children sometimes are temporally punished, for their parent's sins, and the community for their leader's, either for their consent before the fact or after; or to prevent that they do not the like. S. Tho. 2. 2. q. 108.\f*
\v 43 And Bacchides heard it, and he came on the day of the Sabbaths even to the brink of Jordan with a great power:
\v 44 And Jonathas said to his company: Let us arise, and fight against our enemies: for it is not today as yesterday, and the day before.
\v 45 For lo battle directly against us, and the water of Jordan on this side and on that side, and banks, and marishes, & forests: and there is no place to turn aside.
\v 46 Now therefore cry ye unto heaven, that you may be delivered out of the hand of your enemies. And battle was joined. \x + \xo 9:46 \xt 2. Par. 20. v. 3.\x*
\v 47 And Jonathas stretched forth his hand to strike Bacchides, & he turned aside from him backwards.
\v 48 And Jonathas lept aside, and they that were with him into Jordan, & they swam over Jordan to them: \f + \fr 9:48 \ft Ionathas and his men swam not to the other side, but to another place on the same side: for other wise the armies had been parted by the river: and so there had been no conflict that time.\f*
\v 49 and there fell of Bacchides' part that day a thousand men: and they returned into Jerusalem,
\v 50 and built fenced cities in Jurie, the fortress that was in Jericho, and in Ammaum, and in Bethoron, and in Bethel, and Thamnata, and Phara, and Thopo with high walls, and gates, & locks.
\v 51 And he placed a garrison in them, that they might exercise enmities against Israel:
\v 52 and he fenced the city Bethsura, and Gazara, and the castle, and set garrisons in them, & provision of victuals:
\v 53 & he took the sons of the princes of the country for hostages, and put them in the castle in Jerusalem into ward.
\v 54 And in the year an hundred fifty three, the second month, Alcimus commanded the walls of the inner holy house to be destroyed, and the works of the Prophets to be destroyed: & he began to destroy. \f + \fr 9:54 \ft Iosephus li. 12. c. 17. confesseth that Judas was high-Priest, but erreth in saying he succeeded after Alcimus: neither considering that Alcimus was not indeed high priest, but an usurper: nor that he lived after Judas: who was slain a year before this time. v. 3. & 18. Whereby, and by many other such errors, we see that Iosephus is rather to be corrected by this book than to disallow this book because it differeth from Iosephus, or other like authors.\f*
\v 55 In that time was Alcimus strucken: and his works were stayed, and his mouth was stopped, and he was dissolved with the palsy, neither could he speak a word any more, and give commandment touching his house.
\v 56 And Alcimus died at that time with great torment.
\v 57 And Bacchides saw that Alcimus was dead: and he returned to the king, & the land was quiet for two years.
\v 58 And all the wicked thought saying: Behold Jonathas, and they that are with him, dwell in silence securely: now therefore let us bring Bacchides, and he shall take them all in one night.
\v 59 And they went, and gave him counsel.
\v 60 And he arose to come with a great army: and he sent secretly epistles to his fellows that were in Jurie, to take Jonathas, and them that were with him: but they could not, because their counsel was known to them.
\v 61 And he apprehended of the men of the country, that were the principal of the mischief, fifty men, and he slew them.
\v 62 And Jonathas retired aside, and Simon, and they that were with him into Bethbessen, which is in the desert: and he built up the ruins thereof, and they fortified it.
\v 63 And Bacchides understood it, and gathered together all his multitude, and sent word to them that were of Jurie.
\v 64 And he came, and camped above Bethbessen, and assaulted it many days, and made engines.
\v 65 And Jonathas left Simon his brother in the city, and went forth into the country, & came with a number,
\v 66 and struck Odares, and his brethren, and the children of Phaseron in their tabernacles, and he began to slay, and to grow in forces.
\v 67 But Simon and they that were with him, went out of the city, and burnt the engines,
\v 68 and they fought against Bacchides, & he was discomfited by them: and they afflicted him exceedingly, because his counsel, and his conflict was in vain.
\v 69 And being angry against the wicked men, that had given him counsel to come into their country, he slew many of them: but himself thought with the rest to depart into their country. \f + \fr 9:69 \ft Evil councel how soever it happeneth to them that follow it, is ever hurtful to them that give it.\f*
\v 70 And Jonathas understood it, and he sent unto him legates to make peace with him, and to render unto him the captives.
\v 71 And he took it gladly, and did according to his words, and sware that he would do him no harm all the days of his life.
\v 72 And he rendered unto him the captives, which he before had taken for a prey, out of the land of Juda: & returning he departed into his own country, and he added no more to come into their coasts.
\v 73 And the sword ceased out of Israel: and Jonathas dwelt in Machmas, and Jonathas began there to judge the people, and he destroyed the impious out of Israel.
\c 10
\p
\v 0 horsemen) 83. Jonathas burneth Azotus, with their idol \add Dagon: 86. so returneth by Ascalon to Jerusalem with great glory.\add*
\v 1 And in the year an hundreth threescore came up Alexander the son of Antiochus, that was surnamed Noble: and he took Ptolemais, and they received him, and he reigned there. \f + \fr 10:1 \ft He falsely avouched that he was the son of Antiochus Epiphanes: for he was indeed of very mean birth. Iustinus. li. 35.\f*
\v 2 And Demetrius the king heard it, and he gathered together an exceeding great army, and went forth to meet him into battle.
\v 3 And Demetrius sent an epistle to Jonathas in peaceable words, to magnify him.
\v 4 For he said: Let us prevent to make peace with him, before he make with Alexander against us:
\v 5 for he will remember all the evils, that we have done against him, and against his brother, and against his nation.
\v 6 And he gave him authority to gather an army, and to make weapons, and to be himself his fellow: and the hostages that were in the castle, he commanded to be delivered to him.
\v 7 And Jonathas came into Jerusalem, and read the epistles in the hearing of all the people, and of them that were in the castle.
\v 8 And they feared with great fear, because they heard that the king gave him authority to gather an army.
\v 9 And the hostages were delivered to Jonathas, and he rendered them to their parents.
\v 10 And Jonathas dwelt in Jerusalem, and began to build, & to renew the city.
\v 11 And he spake to them that made the works, that they should build the walls, and mount Sion round about with square stones for munition: and so they did.
\v 12 And the Aliens fled that were in the holds, which Bacchides had built:
\v 13 and every man left his place, & departed into his own country:
\v 14 only in Bethsura there remained some of them, that had forsaken the law, and the precepts of God: for this was for a refuge to them.
\v 15 And Alexander the king heard of the promises, that Demetrius had promised to Jonathas: and they told him the battles, & the worthy acts that he did, and his brethren, and the labours, that they endured:
\v 16 and he said: Why, shall we find any such man? And now we will make him a friend, and our fellow.
\v 17 And he wrote an epistle, and sent it to him according to these words, saying:
\v 18 \sc King\sc* Alexander to his brother Jonathas greeting.
\v 19 We have heard of thee, that thou art mighty of power, and art meet to be our friend:
\v 20 and now we make thee this day high Priest of thy nation, that thou be called the king's friend (& he sent him purple, and a crown of gold) & in our affairs thou be of one mind with us, and keep amity towards us. \f + \fr 10:20 \ft It was not in the king's power to make Ionathas high priest but he being so before, the king from this time did so account him.\f*
\v 21 And Jonathas put on him the holy stole the seventh month, in the year an hundreth threescore in the solemn day of Scenopegia: and he gathered an army, and made very many weapons.
\v 22 And Demetrius heard these words, and was exceeding sorry, and said:
\v 23 What is this that we have done, that Alexander hath prevented us to take the friendship of the Jews for his strength?
\v 24 I also will write to them words of request, and dignities, and gifts: that they may be with me to aid me.
\v 25 And he wrote to them in these words: \sc King\sc* Demetrius to the nation of the Jews greeting.
\v 26 Because you have kept covenant towards us, and have continued in our amity, and have not joined to our enemies, we have heard of it, and are glad. \f + \fr 10:26 \ft This King Demetrius to get his desired purpose, sticked not to write a plain lie, for he had heard that the Jews had refused him and made league with his enemy Alexander. v. 22. 23.\f*
\v 27 And now persevere still to keep fidelity towards us, & we will reward you with good things, for that you have done with us.
\v 28 And we will remit you many charges, and will give you many gifts.
\v 29 And now I release you, and all the Jews from tributes, & I pardon you the prices of salt, & remit the crowns, & the thirds of the seed:
\v 30 and the half of the fruit of trees, which is my portion, I leave to you from this day forward, that it be not taken of the land of Juda, and of the three cities that are added thereto of Samaria, & Galilee from this day & for ever:
\v 31 & let Jerusalem be holy, and free with the coasts thereof: & the tithes, & tributes be they to it.
\v 32 I release also the authority of the castle, that is in Jerusalem, and I give it to the high priest, to place therein men whomsoever he shall choose, that may keep it.
\v 33 And every soul of the Jews, that is captive from the land of Juda in all my kingdom, I dismiss free for nothing, that all may be discharged also from tributes of their cattle.
\v 34 And all the solemn days, & the sabbaths, & the new moons, & the days appointed, and three days before the solemn day, and three days after the solemn day let them all be of immunity & remission, to all the Jews that are in my kingdom:
\v 35 & no man shall have power to do any thing, & to make businesses against any of them in any cause.
\v 36 And let there be enrolled of the Jews in the king's army to the number of thirty thousand men: & allowance shall be given them as behoveth to all the king's bands, & of them there shall be ordained certain, that shall be in the fortresses of the great king:
\v 37 and of these there shall be appointed over the affairs of the kingdom, that are done of trust, and let there be princes of them, and let them walk in their own laws, as the king hath commanded in the land of Juda.
\v 38 And the three cities that are added to Jury of the country of Samaria, let them be accounted with Jury: that they may be under one, and obey no other power, but the high priest's:
\v 39 Ptolomais, and the confines thereof, which I have given for a gift to the holies, that are in Jerusalem, to the necessary charges of the holy things.
\v 40 And I give every year fifteen thousand sicles of silver of the king's accounts, that belong to me:
\v 41 & all that is above which they had not rendered, that were over the affairs the years before, from this time they shall give it to the works of the house.
\v 42 And beside these five thousand sicles of silver, which they received of the account of the holies every year: & let these pertain to the priests, that execute the ministry.
\v 43 And whosoever fly into the temple that is in Jerusalem, and in all the coasts thereof, in the king's danger for matter, let them be dismissed, & all things, that they have in my kingdom, let them have it free.
\v 44 And to build or repair the works of the holy places, the charges shall be given of the king's account:
\v 45 and to build the walls in Jerusalem, and to fortify them round about, the charges shall be given of the king's account, and to build the walls in Jurie.
\v 46 But as Jonathas, & the people heard these words, they believed them not, nor received them: because they remembered the great mischief, that he had done in Israel, and had afflicted them exceedingly. \f + \fr 10:46 \ft Notwithstanding the great offers of evil disposed men, Ionathas and all prudent men considering their former wicked deeds do not give credit to glorious words.\f* \f + \fr 10:46 \ft ch. 7. v. 11.\f*
\v 47 And their liking was toward Alexander, because he had been the first mover of the words of peace unto them, & him they aided all days.
\v 48 And king Alexander gathered a great army, & moved the camp near to Demetrius.
\v 49 And the two kings joined battle, and the army of Demetrius fled, & Alexander pursued him, & urged them sore.
\v 50 And the battle grew very sore, till the sun went down: & Demetrius was slain in that day.
\v 51 And Alexander sent legates to Ptolomee king of Ægypt according to these words, saying: \f + \fr 10:51 \ft This Ptolomeus Philometor decided a controversy, that the Jews had the true temple in Jerusalem, and that the Samaritanes' temple in Garizim was schismatical: which he judged, because albeit both pleaded antiquity, yet only the Jews proved by continual succession of high Priests from Aaron, and shewed that the other departed from them, first in the time of Jeroboam, and afterwards built that temple in Garizim, when some were returned from captivity: whereof Josephus writeth. li. 13. c. 6. Antiquit. Our Saviour also judged that the cause of the Jews was better. Ioan. 4. v. 22.\f*
\v 52 \sc Because\sc* I am returned into my Kingdom, and am set in the seat of my fathers, & have obtained the princedom, & have destroyed Demetrius, & possessed our country,
\v 53 and have joined battle with him, and he is destroyed himself, & his camp by us, and we sit in the seat of his kingdom:
\v 54 and now let us make amity one with another: & give me thy daughter to wife, and I will be thy son in law, & I will give thee gifts, and to her dignity.
\v 55 And king Ptolomee answered, saying: \sc Happy\sc* is the day wherein thou art returned to the land of thy fathers, and art set in the seat of their kingdom.
\v 56 And now I will do to thee that which thou hast written: but meet me at Ptolomais, that we may see one another, and I may despouse her to thee as thou hast said.
\v 57 And Ptolomee went out of Ægypt, he & Cleopatra his daughter, & he came to Ptolomais in the year an hundred threescore and two.
\v 58 And Alexander the king met him, & he gave him Cleopatra his daughter: and he made her marriage at Ptolomais, as kings in great glory.
\v 59 And king Alexander wrote to Jonathas, that he should come to meet him.
\v 60 And he went with glory to Ptolomais, & he met there the two kings, & he gave them much silver, & gold, & gifts: & he found grace in their sight.
\v 61 And there assembled against him pestilent men of Israel, wicked men soliciting against him: & the king attended not to them.
\v 62 And he commanded Jonathas to be changed of his garments, & that he should be clothed with purple: and so they did. And the king placed him to sit with himself.
\v 63 And he said to his princes: Go ye out with him into the midst of the city, & proclaim, that no man solicit against him for any matter, & that no man be troublesome unto him for any cause.
\v 64 And it came to pass, as they that solicited saw his glory that was published, & him covered with purple, they all fled: \f + \fr 10:64 \ft When calumniators see that the innocent is justified and honoured, they fail in their heart to proceed against him.\f*
\v 65 & the king magnified him, & wrote him amongst his chief friends, & made him Duke, & partaker of the princedom.
\v 66 And Jonathas returned into Jerusalem with peace & joy.
\v 67 In the year an hundreth sixty five came Demetrius the son of Demetrius from Crete into the land of his fathers.
\v 68 And Alexander the king heard it, & he was very sorry, & returned to Antioch.
\v 69 And Demetrius the king made Apollonius general, who was ruler of Coelesiria: & he gathered a great army, & came to Jamnia: & he sent to Jonathas the high priest,
\v 70 saying: Thou only resistest us, & I am brought into derision, & into reproach, because thou doest exercise power against us in the mountains.
\v 71 Now therefore if thou trust in thy forces, come down to us in the plain, let us compare there one with another: because with me is the force of battles.
\v 72 Ask, & learn who I am, & the rest, that aid me, who also say that your foot cannot stand before our face, because twice have thy fathers been put to flight in their own land:
\v 73 and now how wilt thou be able to abide the horsemen, & so great an army in the plain, where is no stone, nor rock, nor place to fly?
\v 74 But as Jonathas heard the words of Apollonius, he was moved in mind: & he chose ten thousand men, & went forth from Jerusalem, & Simon his brother met him to aid him.
\v 75 And they moved the camp to Joppe, & it shut him out of the city: because the garrison of Apollonius was in Joppe, & he assaulted it.
\v 76 And they that were in the city being put in great fear, opened to him, & Jonathas obtained Joppe.
\v 77 And Apollonius heard it, & he took three thousand horsemen, & a great army.
\v 78 And he went to Azotus as making journey, and immediately he went forth into the plain: because he had a multitude of horsemen, and he trusted in them. And Jonathas pursued him unto Azotus, and they joined battle.
\v 79 And Apollonius left in the camp a thousand horsemen behind them secretly.
\v 80 And Jonathas understood that there was an embushment behind him, and they compassed his camp, and they threw darts upon the people from morning even unto evening.
\v 81 But the people stood, as Jonathas had commanded: and their horses laboured. \f + \fr 10:81 \ft Ionathas set his army in that manner as on every side his men stood in front ready to resist the force of the enemy coming towards them, all their backs so turned within their own squadron, that the enemy could no way enter without present resistance: and so those of the ambushment could only cast darts, but could not break the array of Ionathas' camp, nor make any entrance without their own present death.\f*
\v 82 And Simon put forth his army, and joined it against the legion: for the horsemen were wearied: and they were discomfited by him, and fled.
\v 83 And they that were scattered by the plain, fled into Azotus, and entered into Bethdagon their idol house, there to save themselves.
\v 84 And Jonathas burnt Azotus, and the cities that were round about it, and he took the spoils of them, and the temple of Dagon: and all that fled into it, he burnt with fire.
\v 85 And there were that were slain by the sword, with these that were burnt, almost eight thousand men.
\v 86 And Jonathas removed the camp from thence, and brought it to Ascalon: and they went out of the city to meet him in great glory.
\v 87 And Jonathas returned into Jerusalem with his company, having many spoils.
\v 88 And it came to pass: as Alexander the king heard these words, he added yet to glorify Jonathas.
\v 89 And he sent him a chain of gold, as the custom is to be given to the cousins of kings. And he gave him Accaron and all the borders thereof in possession.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 And the king of Ægypt gathered an army, as the sand that is about the sea shore, and many ships: and he sought to win the kingdom of Alexander by guile, and to add it to his own kingdom. \f + \fr 11:1 \ft By this hyperbolical description (very frequent in holy scripture) is signified that Ptolomeus' army was exceeding great, yea greater than can be easily conceived, and therefore is described by excessive terms.\f*
\v 2 And he went out into Syria with peaceable words, & they opened to him the cities, and met him: because Alexander the king had commanded them to go forth to meet him, for that he was his father in law.
\v 3 But when Ptolomee entered the cities, he put garrisons of soldiers in every city.
\v 4 And as he approached to Azotus, they shewed him the temple of Dagon burnt with fire, and Azotus, & the rest thereof thrown down, and the bodies cast forth, & the graves of them that were slain in the battle, which they had made near the way.
\v 5 And they told the king that Jonathas did these things: to raise envy against him: and the king held his peace.
\v 6 And Jonathas came to meet the king into Joppe with glory, and they saluted one another, and they slept there.
\v 7 And Jonathas went with the king even to the river, that was called Eleutherus, and he returned into Jerusalem.
\v 8 And king Ptolomee obtained the dominion of the cities even to Seleucia by the sea side, and he purposed evil purposes against Alexander.
\v 9 And sent legates to Demetrius, saying: Come, let us make a league between us, and I will give thee my daughter that Alexander hath, and thou shalt reign in the kingdom of thy father.
\v 10 For it repenteth me that I have given him my daughter: for he hath sought to kill me.
\v 11 And he dispraised him, for that he coveted his kingdom,
\v 12 and he took away his daughter, & gave her to Demetrius, and alienated himself from Alexander, and his enmities were made manifest.
\v 13 And Ptolomee entered into Antioch, & he put two crowns upon his head, of Ægypt, & of Asia.
\v 14 But Alexander the king was in Cilicia at that time: because they rebelled that were in those places.
\v 15 And Alexander heard it, and came to him into battle: and Ptolomee the king brought forth an army, and met him with a strong power, and put him to flight.
\v 16 And Alexander fled into Arabia, there to be protected: and king Ptolomee was exalted.
\v 17 And Zabdiel an Arabian took off Alexander's head, & sent it to Ptolomee.
\v 18 And king Ptolomee died the third day: & they that were in the fortresses, perished by them that were within the camp.
\v 19 And Demetrius reigned the year an hundreth sixty seven.
\v 20 In those days Jonathas gathered together them, that were in Jurie, to win the castle in Jerusalem: and they made engines against it.
\v 21 And certain that hated their own nation wicked men, went to king Demetrius, and told him that Jonathas besieged the castle. \f + \fr 11:21 \ft When Pastors endeavour to extirpate sin out of the minds of the people, those that hate godliness, suggest to temporal princes that such spiritual preaching is dangerous to their state.\f*
\v 22 And as he heard it, he was wrath: and forthwith he came to Ptolemais, and wrote to Jonathas, that he should not besiege the castle, but should meet him to talk together in haste.
\v 23 But as Jonathas heard it, he bade them besiege it: and he chose of the ancients of Israel, and of the Priests, and put himself in hazard. \f + \fr 11:23 \ft But zealous men cease not from so necessary a work, because God's word is not tied. 2. Tim. 2.\f*
\v 24 And he took gold, & silver, and raiments, & many other presents, & went to the king to Ptolomais, and he found grace in his sight.
\v 25 And certain wicked men of his nation solicited against him.
\v 26 And the king did to him, as they had done to him which had been before him: and he exalted him in the sight of all his friends, \f + \fr 11:26 \ft And wise Kings will most esteem of such men, knowing that their fidelity towards God, is an assurance that they will also be faithful to Princes.\f*
\v 27 and he established to him the chief Priesthood, & whatsoever other things he had before precious, & he made him the chief of his friends.
\v 28 And Jonathas requested of the king that he would make Jury free, & the three toparchies, and Samaria, & the confines thereof: and he promised him three hundred talents. \f + \fr 11:28 \ft The King had before adjoined principal places to Judea which were called Toparchiæ, that is places of principality, or principal governments: now he granted also immunities to them as to all Judea and Samaria.\f*
\v 29 And the king consented: and he wrote to Jonathas epistles of all these things, containing this tenure.
\v 30 \sc King\sc* Demetrius to his brother Jonathas greeting, and to the nation of the Jews.
\v 31 Acopy of the epistle, which we have written to Lasthenes our parent concerning you, we have sent to you that you might know it.
\v 32 \sc King\sc* Demetrius to Lasthenes his parent greeting.
\v 33 We have determined to do good to the nation of the Jews our friends, & that keep the things that are just with us, for their gentleness which they bear towards us.
\v 34 We have ordained therefore unto them all the coasts of Jurie, & the three cities, Apherema, Lyda, & Ramatha, which are added to Jurie of Samaria, & all their confines, to be sequestered to all them that sacrifice in Jerusalem, for these things, which the king received of them every year, and for the fruits of the land, and of the trees.
\v 35 And other things, that pertained to us of the tithes, and of the tributes, from this time we remit to them: & the salt floors, and the crowns, that were presented to us,
\v 36 we grant all to them, & nothing of these shall be broken from this time, and for ever.
\v 37 Now therefore provide to make a copy of these, and let it be given to Jonathas, & let it be laid in the holy mount, and in a solemn place.
\v 38 And Demetrius the king seeing that the land was quiet in his sight, & nothing resisted him, he dismissed all his army, every man to his place, except the foreign army, which he brought from the isles of the Gentiles: and all the bands of his fathers were enemies to him.
\v 39 And there was one Tryphon of Alexander's part before: and he saw that all the army murmured against Demetrius, & he went to Emalchuel the Arabian, that brought up Antiochus the son of Alexander:
\v 40 And he lay upon him, to deliver this Antiochus unto him, to reign in his father's place: and he declared unto him what great things Demetrius did, and the enmities of his hosts against him. And he tarried there many days.
\v 41 And Jonathas sent to Demetrius the king, that he would cast out them, that were in the castle in Jerusalem, and that were in the holds: because they impugned Israel.
\v 42 And Demetrius sent to Jonathas, saying: I will not only do these things for thee, & for thy nation, but with glory I will honour thee, & thy nation, when it shall be time convenient.
\v 43 Now therefore thou shalt do well if thou wilt send men to help me: because all mine army is departed.
\v 44 And Jonathas sent him three thousand valiant men to Antioch: and they came to the king, & the king was delighted at their coming. \f + \fr 11:44 \ft Three thousand faithful encountering with an hundred & twenty thousand infidels, killed of them in one day an\f*
\v 45 And there assembled they that were of the city, an hundred twenty thousand men, and they would have slain the king.
\v 46 And the king fled into the court: & they that were of the city kept the ways of the city, and began to fight.
\v 47 And the king called the Jews for aid: & they came together to him all at once, & they were all dispersed through the city.
\v 48 And they slew in that day an hundred thousand men, & they burnt the city, & took many spoils in that day, & delivered the king.
\v 49 And they that were of the city saw, that the Jews had obtained the city as they would: and they were discomfited in their mind, and cried to the king with petitions, saying:
\v 50 Give us the right hand, and let the Jews cease to oppugn us & the city.
\v 51 And they threw away their weapons, & made peace, & the Jews were glorified in the king's sight, & were renowned in the sight of all that were in his kingdom, & returned into Jerusalem with many spoils.
\v 52 And king Demetrius sat in the seat of his kingdom: and the land was at rest in his sight.
\v 53 And he feigned all things whatsoever he said, & alienated himself from Jonathas, and he requited him not according to the benefits, that he had given him, and he vexed him exceedingly.
\v 54 And after these things Tryphon returned, & with him Antiochus the young boy, who reigned, and put the crown upon him.
\v 55 And there gathered unto him all the bands, which Demetrius had dispersed, and they fought against him: & he fled, and turned the back.
\v 56 And Tryphon took the beasts, and won Antioch.
\v 57 And Antiochus the young man wrote to Jonathas, saying: I appoint to thee the priesthood, & I place thee over the four cities, that thou mayst be of the king's friends.
\v 58 And he sent him vessels of gold for his service, and he gave him leave to drink in gold, and to be in purple, & to have a chain of gold: \f + \fr 11:58 \ft As to wear purple, and to bare a crown, so to drink in gold cups, and to wear a gold chain, was proper to Kings, and to whom they gave license.\f*
\v 59 And he appointed Simon his brother governor from the borders of Tyre even to the coasts of Ægypt.
\v 60 And Jonathas went forth, & walked through the cities beyond the river: and all the band of Syria gathered unto him to help him, and he came to Ascalon, & they met him honourably out of the city.
\v 61 And he went from thence to Gaza: and they that were in Gaza shut in themselves: and he besieged it, & burnt the things that were round about the city, and he spoiled it.
\v 62 And the men of Gaza besought Jonathas, and he gave them the right hand: and he took their sons for hostages, & sent them into Jerusalem: and he walked through the country even to Damascus.
\v 63 And Jonathas heard that the princes of Demetrius prevaricated in Cades, which is in Galilee, with a great army meaning to remove him from the affairs of the kingdom:
\v 64 and he went against them: but his brother Simon he left within the Province.
\v 65 And Simon approached to Bethsura, and expugned it many days, and inclosed them.
\v 66 And they requested of him to take the right hands, and he gave it them: and he cast them out from thence, and took the city, & placed therein a garrison. \f + \fr 11:66 \ft It is an ancient ceremony in all nations, often mentioned in these Books, to confirm peace by giving each other the right hand.\f*
\v 67 And Jonathas and his camp approached to the water of Genesar, and before it was light they watched in the plain Asor.
\v 68 And lo the camp of the aliens met him in the plain, and they laid embushments for him in the mountains: but he went against them.
\v 69 And the embushments rose out of their places, & they joined battle.
\v 70 And all fled that were on Jonathas' part, and none was left of them, but Mathathias the son of Absolom, and Judas the son of Calphi, chief captain of the chivalry of the host. \f + \fr 11:70 \ft Only two captains remained, and with them some soldiers (as Iosephus writeth about 50.) for it is not to be thought that Ionathas would have returned to battle. v. 72. being but three men in all to begin a new assault.\f*
\v 71 And Jonathas rent his garments, and put earth upon his head, and prayed.
\v 72 And Jonathas returned to them into battle, and he put them to flight, and they fought.
\v 73 And they of his part that fled saw, and returned to him, and pursued with him even to Cades to their camp, and they came even thither.
\v 74 And there fell of the aliens in that day three thousand men: and Jonathas returned into Jerusalem.
\c 12
\p
\v 1 And Jonathas saw that the time helped him, he chose men & sent them to Rome, to establish and to renew amity with them:
\v 2 and to the Spartiates, & to other places he sent epistles according to the same tenure. \f + \fr 12:2 \ft Sparta the chief city of Lacedemonia called also Lacedemon, and Theramne.\f*
\v 3 And they went to Rome, and entered into the court, and said: Jonathas the high priest, and the nation of the Jews have sent us to renew the amity and society according as before.
\v 4 And they gave them epistles unto them by place and place, to conduct them into the land of Juda with peace.
\v 5 And this is a copy of the epistles which Jonathas wrote to the Spartiates:
\v 6 \sc Jonathas\sc* the high Priest, and the ancients of the nation, and the Priests, and the rest of the people of the Jews, to the Spartiates their brethren greeting. \f + \fr 12:6 \ft Spartians otherwise called Lacedemonians (by Iosephus and other writers) descended from Abraham, v. 21. and were in great league with the Jews.\f*
\v 7 Long ago were epistles sent to Onias the high-Priest from Arius who reigned with you, that you are our brethren, as the writing containeth, that here beneath followeth.
\v 8 And Onias received the man that was sent with honour: and he received the epistles, wherein there was signification of the society and amity.
\v 9 We whereas we needed none of these, having for our comfort the holy books, that are in our hands,
\v 10 chose rather to send unto you to renew the fraternity, lest perhaps we be made aliens from you: for much time is passed, since you sent to us.
\v 11 We therefore at all time without intermission in the solemn days, and the rest wherein we should, are mindful of you in the sacrifices, that we offer, and in the observances, as it is meet, and becometh to remember brethren.
\v 12 We rejoice therefore of your glory.
\v 13 But many tribulations have compassed us, and many battles, and the kings that are round about us, have impugned us.
\v 14 We therefore would not be troublesome to you, nor to the rest our fellows & friends in these battles.
\v 15 For we have had aid from heaven, and we are delivered, and our enemies are humbled.
\v 16 We have chosen therefore Numenius the son of Antiochus, and Antipater the son of Jason, and have sent to the Romans to renew with them the old amity and society.
\v 17 We therefore have commanded them that they come unto you also, and salute you, and deliver you our epistles, concerning the renewing of our fraternity.
\v 18 And now you shall do well in answering us to these things.
\v 19 And this is the rescript of the epistles, which he had sent to Onias: \f + \fr 12:19 \ft The Spartians had written this epistle before Onias writ to them, though it be here placed after.\f*
\v 20 \sc Arius\sc* the king of the Spartians to Onias the grand Priest greeting.
\v 21 It is found in scripture of the Spartians, and the Jews, that they are brethren, & that they are of the stock of Abraham. \f + \fr 12:21 \ft There remained with the Spartiates old writs of genealogies, as Iosephus supposeth. li. 12. c. 5. & li. 13. c. 9.\f*
\v 22 And now since we understood these things, you do well in writing to us of your peace.
\v 23 Yea and we have written again to you, Our cattle, and our possessions, are yours: and yours, ours. We therefore have commanded that these things be told you.
\v 24 And Jonathas heard that the princes of Demetrius were come again with a great army more than before to fight against him.
\v 25 And he went out from Jerusalem, & met them in the country of Amathis: for he gave them not space to enter into his country.
\v 26 And he sent spies into their camp, and they returning reported that they appointed to come upon them in the night.
\v 27 And when the sun was set, Jonathas commanded his men to watch, and to be in armour ready to fight all night, and he set watchmen round about the camp.
\v 28 And the adversaries heard that Jonathas with his company was prepared to battle: & they feared & were afraid in their heart: and they kindled fires in their camp.
\v 29 But Jonathas, & they that were with him, knew it not till the morning, and they saw light burning,
\v 30 and Jonathas followed them, & overtook them not: for they had passed the river Eleutherus.
\v 31 And Jonathas turned aside to the Arabians, that were called Zabadeans, & he struck them, & took the spoils of them.
\v 32 And he joined, & came to Damascus, & walked through all that country.
\v 33 But Simon went forth, and came even to Ascalon, and to the next holds, and he declined into Joppe, and took it.
\v 34 (For he heard that they would deliver the hold to Demetrius' part) and he put a garrison there to keep it.
\v 35 And Jonathas returned, and called together the ancients of the people, & he consulted with them to build fortresses in Jurie,
\v 36 & to build the walls in Jerusalem, and to rear a mount of a great height between the castle and the city, to separate it from the city, that it might be alone, and they might neither buy nor sell:
\v 37 And they came together to build the city: and the wall fell that was upon the torrent toward the rising of the sun, and he repaired it, which is called Caphetetha:
\v 38 and Simon built Adiada in Sephela, and fortified it, and hanged on gates & locks.
\v 39 And when Tryphon had purposed to reign over Asia, and to take the crown, and to extend his hand against Antiochus the king: \f + \fr 12:39 \ft Morally in Tryphon is noted the practice of the devil: who intending to overthrow a King or a Kingdom, first seeketh to deceive the pastors, and to destroy them: especially by error or other sin. For (as S. Gregory teacheth. ho. 38. ) if the pastor's life be corrupted, his doctrine will be contemned.\f*
\v 40 fearing lest perhaps Jonathas would not permit him, but would fight against him, he sought to take him and to kill him. And rising up he went into Bethsan.
\v 41 And Jonathas went forth to meet him with forty thousand chosen men into battle, and came to Bethsan.
\v 42 And Tryphon saw that Jonathas came with a great army, to extend his hands upon him: and he feared:
\v 43 and received him with honour, & commanded him to all his friends, and gave him gifts: and he commanded his hosts to obey him, as himself.
\v 44 And he said to Jonathas: Why hast thou troubled all the people, whereas we have no war?
\v 45 And now send them back to their houses, but choose thee a few men, that may be with thee, and come with me to Ptolomais, and I will deliver it to thee, and the other holds, and the army, and all the overseers of the affairs, and returning I will depart: for therefore I came.
\v 46 And Jonathas believed him, and did as he said: and dismissed his army, and they departed into the land of Juda:
\v 47 but he retained with him three thousand men: of whom he sent back two thousand into Galilee, and a thousand came with him.
\v 48 But as Jonathas entered into Ptolemais, they of Ptolemais shut the gates of the city, and they took him, and all that had entered with him they slew with the sword.
\v 49 And Tryphon sent an army and horsemen into Galilee, and into the great plain to destroy all Jonathas' fellows.
\v 50 But they when they understood that Jonathas was taken, & was perished, and all that were with him, they encouraged themselves, and went forth ready to battle.
\v 51 And these that had pursued, seeing that the matter stood upon their life, they returned.
\v 52 But they came all with peace into the land of Juda. And they lamented Jonathas, & them that were with him exceedingly: and Israel mourned with great mourning.
\v 53 And all the heathen that were round about them, sought to destroy them, for they said:
\v 54 They have no prince, and helper: now therefore let us expugn them, and take away from men the memory of them.
\c 13
\p
\v 1 And Simon heard that Tryphon gathered a very great army, to come into the land of Juda, and to destroy it. \f + \fr 13:1 \ft Simon the fourth general captain of the Machabees, & high-priest excelled his brethren in wisdom, by the testimony of his father, c. 2. v. 65.\f*
\v 2 Seeing that the people was in dread, and in fear, he went up to Jerusalem, and assembled the people:
\v 3 and exhorting he said: You know what great battles I and my brethren, and the house of my father have made for the laws, and the holies, and the distresses that we have seen:
\v 4 by reason of these are all my brethren perished for Israel, and I only am left.
\v 5 And now let it not fall to me to spare my life in all time of tribulation: for I am not better than my brethren.
\v 6 I will avenge therefore my nation and the holies, our children also, and wives: because all the heathen are gathered together to destroy us of enmity. \f + \fr 13:6 \ft He undertook by all his endeavour to defend and deliver his nation from danger and to restore their former liberty.\f*
\v 7 And the spirit of the people was kindled as soon as they heard these words:
\v 8 and they answered with a loud voice, saying: Thou art our captain in the place of Judas, and Jonathas thy brother:
\v 9 fight thou our battle, and we will do all things whatsoever thou shalt say to us.
\v 10 And gathering together all the men of war, he hastened to finish all the walls of Jerusalem, and fortified it round about.
\v 11 And he sent Jonathas the son of Absalom, and with him a new army into Joppe, and they that were in the castle being cast out, he remained there.
\v 12 And Tryphon removed from Ptolemais with a great army, to come into the land of Juda, and Jonathas with him in ward.
\v 13 But Simon pitched in Addus against the face of the plain.
\v 14 And as Tryphon understood that Simon was risen in the place of his brother Jonathas: and that he would join battle with him, he sent legates to him,
\v 15 saying: For the silver, that thy brother Jonathas owed in the king's account, for the affairs which he had, we have stayed him.
\v 16 And now send an hundred talents of silver, and his two sons for hostages, that being dismissed he fly not from us, and we will release him.
\v 17 And Simon knew that with guile he spake with him, nevertheless he commanded the silver, and the children to be given: lest he should get great enmity with the people of Israel, saying: \f + \fr 13:17 \ft Simon being wise chose the less evil, and less danger. For if he had not sent that was demanded, it was very like and almost certain, that Ionathas should be slain, and it would have been imputed to Simon, that he had not taken just care of his brother's life, whereby the people would have been alienated from him, and perhaps have revolted from him, and also from religion. S. Tho. in hunc locum.\f*
\v 18 Because he sent not the silver, and the children, therefore is he perished.
\v 19 And he sent the children, and the hundred talents: and he lied, and dismissed not Jonathas.
\v 20 And after these things came Tryphon within the country, to destroy it, and they compassed by the way that leadeth to Addar, and Simon, & his camp marched into every place whither soever they went.
\v 21 And they that were in the castle sent legates to Tryphon, that he should hasten to come through the desert, and should send them victuals.
\v 22 And Tryphon prepared all the horsemen to come that night: but there was an exceeding great snow, and he came not into the country of Galaad.
\v 23 And when he had approached to Bascama, he slew Jonathas and his sons there.
\v 24 And Tryphon returned, and went into his country.
\v 25 And Simon sent and took the bones of Jonathas his brother, and buried them in Modin the city of his fathers.
\v 26 And all Israel lamented him with great lamentation: and they mourned for him many days.
\v 27 And Simon built over the sepulchre of his father and of his brethren a building high to behold, of stone polished behind and before: \f + \fr 13:27 \ft This was not vain glory, but true glory to keep memory of so great virtue: thereby to stir up others to imitation. He that loveth honour (saith S. Augustin. li. cont. Secundin. c. 17. ) imitateth God. but humble souls desire honour in God, proud men will be honoured more than God. or without God. O how many Epitaphs are of wicked men, nothing else but perpetual monuments of their ambition, vanity, injustice, cruelty, & other vices! But those that are of true virtues are to God's more honour: the author of all virtues.\f*
\v 28 and he erected seven spires one against one, to his father and mother, and to his four brethren:
\v 29 and about these he set great pillars: and upon the pillars armour for an eternal memory: and by the armour ships graven, which might be seen of all that sailed the sea.
\v 30 This is the sepulchre, that he made in Modin even until this day.
\v 31 But Tryphon when he journeyed with Antiochus the king, being but a young man, by guile he slew him.
\v 32 And he reigned in his place, & put the crown of Asia upon himself, and made a great plague in the land.
\v 33 And Simon built the fortresses of Jurie, fortifying them with high towers, & great walls, and gates, and locks: and he put victuals in the fortresses.
\v 34 And Simon chose men & sent to Demetrius the king, that he would make a release to the country: because all Tryphon's acts had been done by spoil.
\v 35 And Demetrius the king according to these words answered him, and wrote an epistle in this manner:
\v 36 \sc King\sc* Demetrius to Simon the High-Priest, and the friend of kings, and to the ancients, and to the nation of the Jews, greeting.
\v 37 The crown of gold, and the bahem, which you sent, we have received: and we are ready to make with you great peace, and to write to the king's chief officers to release you the things that we have released. \f + \fr 13:37 \ft * a precious chain.\f*
\v 38 For whatsoever things we have decreed unto you, stand in force. The holds that you have built, let them be to you.
\v 39 We remit also the ignorances, and offences even until this day, and the crown which you owed: and if any other thing was tributary in Jerusalem, now let it not be tributary.
\v 40 And if any of you be fit to be enrolled among ours, let them be enrolled and let there be peace between us.
\v 41 In the year an hundreth seventy was the yoke of the Gentiles taken away from Israel.
\v 42 And the people of Israel began to write in the tables, and public instruments. The first year under Simon the High-Priest, the great Duke, and the Prince of the Jews:
\v 43 In these days Simon approached to Gaza, and compassed it with camps, and he made engines, and set them to the city, and he struck one tower, and took it.
\v 44 And they that were within the engine, brake out into the city: and there was made a great stir in the city.
\v 45 And they that were in the city went up with their wives and children upon the wall their coats rent, and they cried with a loud voice, desiring of Simon that the right hands might be given them,
\v 46 and they said: Requite us not according to our malices, but according to thy mercies.
\v 47 And Simon yielding destroyed them not: but yet he cast them out of the city, and cleansed the houses, wherein there had been idols, and then he entered into it with hymns blessing our Lord: \f + \fr 13:47 \ft By how much more, that mercy is admixed with justice, so that justice be not destroyed, and that religion be advanced, the better it pleaseth God, and edifieth the well disposed.\f*
\v 48 and all filthiness being cast out of it, he placed in it men that should do the law: and he fortified it, and made it his habitation.
\v 49 But they that were in the castle of Jerusalem, were prohibited to go out and to come into the country, and to buy and sell: and they were exceeding hungry, and many of them perished for famine,
\v 50 and they cried to Simon to receive the right hands, and he gave it them: and he cast them out from thence, and cleansed the castle from the contaminations:
\v 51 and they entered into it the three and twentieth day of the second month, the year an hundreth seventy one, with praise, and boughs of palm trees, and harps, and cymbals, and nables, and hymns, and canticles, because the great enemy was destroyed out of Israel.
\v 52 And he ordained that every year these days should be kept with gladness.
\v 53 And he fortified the mount of the temple, that was by the castle, and he dwelt there himself, & they that were with him.
\v 54 And Simon saw John his son, that he was a valiant man of war: and he made him captain of all the hosts: and he dwelt in Gazara. \f + \fr 13:54 \ft This John Hyrcanus defended the country against invaders. ch. 16.\f*
\c 14
\p
\v 1 In the year an hundreth seventy two, king Demetrius gathered his army, and went into Media to get him aids to expugn Tryphon.
\v 2 And Arsaces the king of Persia, and Media heard, that Demetrius was entered his confines, and he sent one of his princes to take him alive.
\v 3 And he went, and struck the camp of Demetrius: and took him, and brought him to Arsaces, and he put him into ward.
\v 4 And all the land of Juda was at rest all the days of Simon, and he sought good to his nation: & his power, and his glory pleased them all days. \f + \fr 14:4 \ft Simon had now governed the people two years, beginning with great difficulties, but henceforth enjoyed peace till Antiochus Sedetes brake the league, & invaded Jury. ch. 15. v. 27. & 39.\f*
\v 5 And with all his glory he took Joppe for an haven, and made it an entrance unto the isles of the sea.
\v 6 And he enlarged the borders of his nation, and obtained the country:
\v 7 And gathered a great captivity, and had dominion of Gazara, and of Bethsura, and of the castle: and took away the uncleanness out of it, and there was none that resisted him. \f + \fr 14:7 \ft He reduced many Jews from captivity.\f*
\v 8 And every man tilled his land with peace: and the land of Juda yielded her fruits, and the trees of the fields their fruit.
\v 9 The ancients sat all in the streets, and treated of the good things of the land, and the youngmen did on them glory, and the stoles of war.
\v 10 And he gave victuals to the cities, and he appointed them that they should be vessels of munition, till the name of his glory was renowned even to the end of the earth.
\v 11 He made peace upon the land, and Israel rejoiced with great joy.
\v 12 And every man sat under his vine, and under his figtree: and there was none to make them afraid.
\v 13 There was none left that impugned them upon the earth: kings were discomfited in those days.
\v 14 And he confirmed all the humble of his people, and sought the law, & took away every wicked and evil man:
\v 15 he glorified the holies, and multiplied the vessels of the holy places.
\v 16 And it was heard at Rome that Jonathas was dead, & even unto the Spartiates: and they were very sorry.
\v 17 But as they heard that Simon his brother was made the High-Priest in his place, and he obtained all the country, and the cities therein;
\v 18 they wrote to him in brazen tables, to renew the amities and society, which they had made with Judas, & with Jonathas his brethren.
\v 19 And they were read in the sight of the Church in Jerusalem. And this is a copy of the epistles, that the Spartiates sent.
\v 20 \sc The Princes\sc* and the cities of the Spartians to Simon the grand Priest, & to the ancients, and the Priests, and the rest of the people of the Jews their brethren, greeting. \f + \fr 14:20 \ft Sparta being the chief city of Lacedemonia, had many cities subject & depending as upon their Metropolitan.\f*
\v 21 The legates, that were sent to our people, have told us of your glory, and honour, and joy: and we rejoiced at their entrance.
\v 22 And we wrote that, which was said of them in the counsels of the people, thus: Numenius the son of Antiochus, and Antipater the son of Jason, legates of the Jews, came to us, renewing with us old amity.
\v 23 And it pleased the people to receive the men gloriously, and to put a copy of their words in the severed book of the people, to be for a memory to the people of the Spartiates. And a copy of these we have written to Simon the grand Priest.
\v 24 And after these things Simon sent Numenius to Rome, having a great buckler of gold, of the weight of thousand pounds, to establish amity with them. But when the people of Rome had heard \f + \fr 14:24 \ft When peace was established in all Jury, and friendship confirmed with the Romans, & Lacedemonians, the whole nation of the Jews in gratitude towards Simon, who only now remained of Mathathias' sons, confirmed him in the office of high-priest perpetually or for ever, v. 41. that is, during his life, & to his progeny, v. 49.\f*
\v 25 these words, they said: What thanks-giving shall we render to Simon & his children?
\v 26 For he hath restored his brethren, and hath expugned the enemies of Israel from them: and they decreed him liberty, & registered it in tables of brass, & put it in titles in mount Sion.
\v 27 And this is a copy of the writing. \sc The Eighteenth\sc* day of the month Elul, in the year an hundreth seventy two, the third year under Simon the grand-Priest in Asaramel,
\v 28 in a great assembly of the Priests, and of the people & the Princes of the nation, and the ancients of the country, these things were notified: that there have often been battles made in our country.
\v 29 But Simon the son of Mathathias of the children of Jarib, & his brethren put themselves in danger, and resisted the adversaries of their nation, that their holies and law might stand: and with great glory have they glorified their nation.
\v 30 And Jonathas gathered together his nation, & was made their grand Priest, & he was laid to his people.
\v 31 And their enemies would conculcate, and destroy their country, and extend their hands against the holies.
\v 32 Then Simon, resisted and fought for his nation, and bestowed much money, and armed the valiant men of his nation, and gave them wages:
\v 33 and he fortified the cities of Jurie, and Bethsura, that was in the borders of Jurie, where the armour of the enemies was before: and he placed there Jews for a garrison.
\v 34 And he fortified Joppe, which was by the sea: and Gazara, which is in the borders of Azotus, wherein the enemies dwelt before, and he placed Jews there: and whatsoever was fit for their correption, he put in them.
\v 35 And the people saw the fact of Simon, and the glory that he meant to do to his nation, and they made him their duke, and grand Priest, for that he had done all these things, and for the justice, and faith, which he kept to his nation, and for that he sought by all means to advance his people.
\v 36 And in his days it prospered in his hands, so that the heathen were taken away out of their country, and they that were in the city of David in Jerusalem in the castle, out of which they came forth, and contaminated all things that were round about the holies, and they brought great plague upon chastity:
\v 37 and he placed in it men of Jurie to the defence of the country, and of the city, and he raised the walls of Jerusalem.
\v 38 And king Demetrius appointed him the high priesthood.
\v 39 According to these things he made him his friend, and glorified him with great glory.
\v 40 For he heard that the Jews were called of the Romans, friends, & fellows, & brethren, & that they received Simon's legates gloriously:
\v 41 and that the Jews, and their Priests consented that he should be their duke, & high-Priest for ever, till there rise the faithful Prophet: \f + \fr 14:41 \ft The high-Priesthood continued in this family of the Machabees until Herod took it from them, selling it for money, and then shortly came Christ the faithful Prophet.\f*
\v 42 and that he be duke over them, and that he should have the care of the holies, and that he should appoint rulers over their works, and over the country, and over the armour, and over the holds.
\v 43 And that he have care of the holies: and that he be heard of all, and that all writings in the country be written in his name: and that he be clothed with purple and gold:
\v 44 and that it be not lawful for any of the people, and of the Priests to disannul any of these, and to gainsay those things, that are said of him, or to call together an assembly in the country without him: & to be clothed with purple, & to wear a chain of gold.
\v 45 But he that shall do beside these things, or shall make frustrate any of these, he shall be guilty.
\v 46 And it pleased all the people to appoint Simon, and to do according to these words.
\v 47 And Simon took it upon him, and it pleased him to execute high Priest-hood, and to be duke & prince of the nation of the Jews, and of the Priests, and to be chief over all.
\v 48 And this writing they bade them put in tables of brass, and to set them in the circuit of the holies, in a famous place:
\v 49 and to put a copy thereof in the treasury, that Simon may have it, and his children.
\c 15
\p
\v 1 And king Antiochus the son of Demetrius sent epistles from the isles of the sea to Simon the priest, and prince of the nation of the Jews, and to all the nation: \f + \fr 15:1 \ft This Antiochus Sedetes son of Demetrius Soter, was brother to Demetrius the second, who was now captive in Persia. ch. 14. v. 3.\f*
\v 2 and they contained this tenure: \sc King\sc* Antiochus to Simon the grand-Priest, and to the nation of the Jews greeting.
\v 3 Because certain pestilent men have obtained the kingdom of our fathers, and I mean to challenge the kingdom, and to restore it as it was before: and I have chosen a great army, and have made ships of war.
\v 4 And I will march through the country, that I may take revenge of them, that have destroyed our country, and that have made many cities desolate in my realm.
\v 5 Now therefore I establish unto thee all the oblations, which all the kings before me remitted unto thee, & what other gifts soever they remitted thee:
\v 6 and I permit thee to make a coin of thy own money in thy country:
\v 7 and Jerusalem to be holy and free, and all the armour that is made, and the fortresses which thou hast built, and which thou dost hold, let them remain to thee.
\v 8 And all that is due to the king, and the things that are to be the king's hereafter, from this present and for all time, they are remitted to thee.
\v 9 And when we shall have obtained our kingdom, we will glorify thee, and thy nation, & the temple with great glory, so that your glory shall be made manifest in all the earth.
\v 10 In the year an hundreth seventy four went forth Antiochus into the land of his fathers, and all the hosts assembled unto him, so that there were few left with Tryphon.
\v 11 And Antiochus the king pursued him, and he came to Dora flying by the sea coast.
\v 12 For he knew that evils were heaped upon him, and the army forsook him.
\v 13 And Antiochus camped upon Dora with an hundred twenty thousand men of war, & eight thousand horsemen:
\v 14 and he compassed the city, and the ships approached to the sea: & they vexed the city by land & by sea, and suffered none to come in, or to go out.
\v 15 And Numenius came, and they that had been with him, from the city of Rome, having epistles written to kings, and countries, wherein were contained these words: \f + \fr 15:15 \ft This legate was sent almost two years before to Rome ch. 14. v. 24. and now brought letters not only to the Jews but also to sundry kings and peoples in their behalf.\f*
\v 16 \sc Lucius\sc* the Consul of the Romans, to Ptolemee the king greeting.
\v 17 The Ambassadors of the Jews our friends came to us, renewing the old amity, and society, being sent from Simon the prince of the priests, and the people of the Jews.
\v 18 And they brought also a buckler of gold of a thousand pounds.
\v 19 It hath pleased us therefore to write to the kings, & countries, that they do them no harm, nor impugn them, & their cities, and their countries: and that they give no aid to them that fight against them.
\v 20 And it hath seemed good unto us to take the buckler of them.
\v 21 If therefore any pestilent men are fled out of their country to you, deliver them to Simon the Prince of the Priests, that he may punish them according to their law.
\v 22 These self same things were written to Demetrius the king, and to Attalus, and to Ariarathes, and to Arsaces,
\v 23 and into all countries: and to Lampsaces, & to the Spartiates, and to Delus, and to Myndus, and to Sicyon, & to Caria, and to Samus, & Pamphilia, and Lycia, and Alicarnassus, and Coo, & Siden, & Aradon, and Rhodes, and Phaselis, & Gortyna, and Gnidus, and Cypres, & Cyrenee.
\v 24 And a copy thereof they wrote to Simon the prince of the priests and people of the Jews.
\v 25 But king Antiochus moved his camp unto Dora the second time, setting hands always upon it, and making engines: & he shut up Tryphon, that he could not go forth.
\v 26 And Simon sent unto him two thousand chosen men for aid, and silver, & gold, and aboundance of furniture.
\v 27 And he would not take them, but brake all things that he covenanted with him before, and alienated himself from him.
\v 28 And he sent to him Athenobius one of his friends, to treat with him, saying: You hold Joppe, and Gazara, and the castle, that is in Jerusalem, cities of my kingdom:
\v 29 their borders you have made desolate, and you have made a great plague in the land, and have ruled in many places in my kingdom.
\v 30 Now therefore deliver the cities, that you have taken, and the tributes of the places, wherein you have ruled without the borders of Jury.
\v 31 But if not, give you for them five hundred talents of silver, and for the destruction, that you have made, & the tributes of cities other five hundred talents: but if not, we will come and expugn you.
\v 32 And Athenobius the king's friend came into Jerusalem, and saw the glory of Simon, and his magnificence in gold, and silver, and furniture aboundant, and he was astonished, & told him the king's words.
\v 33 And Simon answered him, and said to him: Neither have we taken other men's land, neither do we hold that is other men's: but the inheritance of our fathers, which was a certain season unjustly possessed of our enemies.
\v 34 But we having opportunity challenge the inheritance of our fathers.
\v 35 For concerning Joppe, and Gazara, that thou complainest they made a great plague among the people, and in our country: for these we given an hundred talents. And Athenobius answered him not a word. \f + \fr 15:35 \ft we given an hundred talents. And Athenobius answered him not a word.\f*
\v 36 But with anger returning to the king, he reported unto him these words, and the glory of Simon, and all things that he saw, and the king was wrath with great anger.
\v 37 And Tryphon fled by ship to Orthosias
\v 38 And the king appointed Cendebæus captain by the sea coast, and gave him an army of foot men and horsemen.
\v 39 And he commanded him to move the camp against the face of Jurie: and he commanded him to build Cedron, and to fortify the gates of the city, and to conquer the people. But the king pursued Tryphon. \f + \fr 15:39 \ft By the river of Cedron (over which David passed 2. Reg. 15. v. 23. and our Saviour. Ioa. 18. ) a city was now built, or rather repaired being decayed before.\f*
\v 40 And Cendebæus came to Jamnia, and began to provoke the people, and to conculcate Jurie, & to take the people captive, and to kill, and to build Cedron.
\v 41 And he placed there horsemen, and an host: that going forth they might walk by the way of Jurie, as the king appointed him.
\c 16
\p
\v 1 And John went up from Gazara, and told Simon his father what Cendebæus did among their people. \f + \fr 16:1 \ft After Simon's death, his eldest son John, surnamed Hyrcanus, succeeded him in government spiritual and temporal. v. 24.\f*
\v 2 And Simon called his two elder sons, Judas and John, and he said to them: I and my brethren, and the house of my father, have expugned the enemies of Israel from our youth even to this day: and it hath prospered in our hands to deliver Israel oftentimes.
\v 3 And now I am old, but be you in place of me, and my brethren, and going forth fight for our nation: and the help from heaven be with you.
\v 4 And he chose out of the country twenty thousand fighting men and horsemen, and they went forth to Cendebæus: and they slept in Modin.
\v 5 And they arose in the morning, and went into the plain field: and lo a mighty great army coming to meet them of foot men, and horsemen, & there was a running river between them.
\v 6 And he camped against the face of them, himself and his people, and he saw the people fearful to pass through the torrent, and he passed through first: and the men saw him, and they passed over after him.
\v 7 And he divided the people, and the horsemen in the midst of the footmen: and the horsemen of the adversaries were exceeding many.
\v 8 And they sounded with the holy trumpets: and Cendebæus was put to flight, and his camp: and there fell many of them wounded, & the rest fled into the hold.
\v 9 Then was Judas John's brother wounded: But John pursued them, till he came to Cedron, which he built:
\v 10 and they fled even to the towers, that were in the fields of Azotus, and he burnt them with fire. And there fell of them two thousand men, and he returned into Jurie in peace.
\v 11 And Ptolomee the son of Abobus was appointed captain in the plain of Jericho, and he had much silver, & gold.
\v 12 For he was the son in law of the high-Priest.
\v 13 And his heart was exalted, and he would gain the country, and he purposed treachery against Simon and his sons to dispatch them.
\v 14 And Simon walking through the cities, that were in the country of Jurie, and being careful of them, went down into Jericho, he and Mathathias his son, and Judas, the year an hundreth seventy seven, the eleventh month: this is the month Sabath.
\v 15 And the son of Abobus received them with guile into a little fortress, that is called Doch, which he built, and he made them a great feast, and hid men there.
\v 16 And when Simon was inebriated & his sons, Ptolomee arose with his company, and they took their weapons, and entered into the feast, and slew him, and his two sons, and certain of his servants. \f + \fr 16:16 \ft He beginning to govern in the year 170. ch. 13. v. 41. 42. had difficulties the first & last years, in the rest they had peace. To be inebriated signifieth no more but to be replenished with drink competently, or aboundantly, without excess. As Psal. 64. v. 10. the earth inebriated, and v. 11. rivers inebriated. That is, abundantly replenished without excess. S. August. q. 144. in Gen.\f*
\v 17 And he did great deceit in Israel, and rendered evil for good.
\v 18 And Ptolomee wrote these things, and sent to the king that he should send him an army for aid, and he would deliver him the country, and their cities, and tributes.
\v 19 And he sent others into Gazara to dispatch John: and to the tribunes he sent epistles, that they should come to him, and he would give them silver, and gold, and gifts.
\v 20 And he sent others to take Jerusalem, and the mount of the temple.
\v 21 And one running before told John in Gazara, that his father was perished, and his brethren, and that he hath sent that thou also mayst be slain.
\v 22 But as he heard it, he was exceedingly afraid: and he apprehended the men, that came to destroy him, and he slew them: for he knew that they sought to destroy him.
\v 23 And the rest concerning the words of John, and his battles, and the valiant acts, which he did manfully, and the building of the walls, which he built, and the things that he did:
\v 24 lo these are written in the book of the days of his priesthood, from the time that he was made prince of the priests after his father. \f + \fr 16:24 \ft Out of the book here mentioned some think the fourth book of Machabees was translated. See Sixtus Senen. li. 1. Biblioth. pag. 37.\f* \f + \fr 16:24 \ft * li. 2. c. 1. v. 1.\f*
